# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1966-fifa-world-cup-final
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It is over 300 years old, is a Grade I listed building, and contains approximately 100 rooms.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A private residence for the prime minister occupies the third floor and there is a kitchen in the basement.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The other floors contain offices and conference, reception, sitting and dining rooms where the prime minister works, and where government ministers, national leaders, and foreign dignitaries are met and hosted.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] At the rear is an interior courtyard and a terrace overlooking a 1⁄2-acre (0.2 ha) garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Number 10 is adjacent to St James's Park, approximately 3⁄4 mile (1.2 km) from Buckingham Palace, the official residence of the British monarch in London, and is near the Palace of Westminster, the meeting place of both Houses of Parliament.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Originally three houses, Number 10 was offered to Robert Walpole by King George II in 1732.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Walpole accepted on the condition that the gift was to the office of First Lord of the Treasury.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The post of First Lord of the Treasury has, for much of the 18th and 19th centuries and invariably since 1905, been held by the prime minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Walpole commissioned William Kent to join the three houses and it is this larger house that is known as Number 10 Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Despite its size and convenient location near to Parliament, few early prime ministers lived at 10 Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Costly to maintain, neglected, and run-down, Number 10 was scheduled to be demolished several times, but the property survived and became linked with many statesmen and events in British history.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1985 Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Number 10 had become "one of the most precious jewels in the national heritage".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Prime Minister's Office, for which the terms *Downing Street* and *Number 10* are metonyms, lies within the 10 Downing Street building and is part of the Cabinet Office.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It is staffed by civil servants and special advisers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street is property of His Majesty's Government.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Its registered legal title is held in the name of the secretary of state for housing, communities and local government, and the secretary of state is a corporation sole.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Number 10 Downing Street was originally three properties: a mansion overlooking St James's Park called "the House at the Back", a town house behind it, and a cottage.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The town house, from which the modern building gets its name, was one of several built by Sir George Downing, 1st Baronet between 1682 and 1684.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Downing, a noted spy for Oliver Cromwell and later King Charles II, invested in property and acquired considerable wealth.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1654, he purchased the lease on land south of St James's Park, adjacent to the House at the Back within walking distance of parliament.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Downing planned to build a row of terraced town houses "for persons of good quality to inhabit in ..." The street on which he built them now bears his name, and the largest became part of Number 10 Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Straightforward as the investment seemed, it proved otherwise.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Hampden family had a lease on the land that they refused to relinquish.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Downing fought their claim, but failed and had to wait 30 years before he could build.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When the Hampden lease expired, Downing received permission to build on land further west to take advantage of more recent property developments.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The new warrant issued in 1682 reads: "Sir George Downing ... [is authorised] to build new and more houses ... subject to the proviso that it be not built any nearer than 14 feet of the wall of the said Park at the West end thereof".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Between 1682 and 1684, Downing built a cul-de-sac of two-storey town houses with coach-houses, stables and views of St James's Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Over the years, the addresses changed several times.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Downing employed Christopher Wren to design the houses.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Although large, they were put up quickly and cheaply on soft soil with shallow foundations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Winston Churchill wrote that Number 10 was "shaky and lightly built by the profiteering contractor whose name they bear".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The upper end of the Downing Street cul-de-sac closed off the access to St James's Park, making the street quiet and private.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] An advertisement in 1720 described it as "a pretty open Place, especially at the upper end, where are four or five very large and well-built Houses, fit for Persons of Honour and Quality; each House having a pleasant Prospect into St James's Park, with a Tarras Walk".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The cul-de-sac had several distinguished residents: George Granville, 1st Baron Lansdowne from 1692 to 1696 and the Earl of Grantham from 1699 to 1703.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1675, he retired to Cambridge, where he died in 1684, a few months after building was completed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1800, the wealth he had accumulated was used to found Downing College, Cambridge, as had been his wish should his descendants fail in the male line.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Downing's portrait hangs in the entrance hall of Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The "House at the Back", the largest of the three houses which were combined to make Number 10, was a mansion built in about 1530 next to the Palace of Whitehall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Rebuilt, expanded, and renovated many times since, it was originally one of several buildings that made up the "Cockpit Lodgings", so-called because they were attached to an octagonal structure used for cock-fighting.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Early in the 17th century, the Cockpit was converted to a concert hall and theatre; after the Glorious Revolution of 1688, some of the first cabinet meetings were held there secretly.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] For many years, the "House at the Back" was the home of Thomas Knyvet, Keeper of Whitehall Palace, famous for capturing Guy Fawkes in 1605 and foiling his plot to assassinate King James I.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The previous year, Knyvet had moved into a house next door, approximately where Number 10 is today.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] From that time, the "House at the Back" was usually occupied by members of the royal family or the government.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Princess Elizabeth, eldest daughter of King James I, lived there from 1604 until 1613 when she married Frederick V, Elector Palatine and moved to Heidelberg.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] She was the grandmother of King George I, the Elector of Hanover, who became King of Great Britain in 1714, and was a great-grandmother of King George II, who presented the house to Walpole in 1732.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] George Monck, 1st Duke of Albemarle, the general responsible for the Restoration of the Monarchy in 1660, lived there from 1660 until his death in 1671.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] As head of the Great Treasury Commission of 1667–1672, Albemarle transformed accounting methods and allowed the Crown greater control over expenses.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] His secretary, George Downing, who built Downing Street, is thought to have created these changes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Albemarle is the first treasury minister to have lived in what became the home of the First Lord of the Treasury and prime minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1671, George Villiers, 2nd Duke of Buckingham took possession when he joined the Cabal Ministry.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] At considerable expense, Buckingham rebuilt the house.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The result was a spacious mansion, lying parallel to Whitehall Palace with a view of St James Park from its garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] After Buckingham retired in 1676, Lady Charlotte Fitzroy, Charles II's daughter, moved in when she married Edward Lee, 1st Earl of Lichfield.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Crown authorised extensive rebuilding which included adding a storey, thus giving it three main floors, an attic and basement.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This structure can be seen today as the rear section of Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] *(See Plan of the Premises Granted to the Earl and Countess of Lichfield in 1677)* The likely reason that repair was required is that the house had settled in the swampy ground near the Thames, causing structural damage.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Like Downing Street, it rested on a shallow foundation, a design error that caused problems until 1960 when the modern Number 10 was rebuilt on deep pilings.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Lichfields followed James II into exile after the Glorious Revolution.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Two years later in 1690, William III and Mary II gave the "House at the Back" to Hendrik van Nassau-Ouwerkerk, a Dutch general who had assisted in securing the Crown for the Prince of Orange.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Nassau, who Anglicised his name to "Overkirk", lived there until his death in 1708.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The "House at the Back" reverted to the Crown when Lady Overkirk died in 1720.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Treasury issued an order "for repairing and fitting it up in the best and most substantial manner" at a cost of £2,522.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The name of the "House at the Back" changed with the occupant, from Lichfield House to Overkirk House in 1690 to Bothmer House in 1720.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Johann Caspar von Bothmer, Premier Minister of the Electorate of Hanover, head of the German Chancery and adviser to George I and II, took up residency in 1720.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Although Bothmer complained about "the ruinous Condition of the Premises", he lived there until his death in 1732.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Even though Count von Bothmer was not British, he was a subject of George I and George II and the first politician and head of a government who resided in 10 Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When Count Bothmer died, ownership of the "House at the Back" reverted to the Crown.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] George II took this opportunity to offer it to Robert Walpole, often called the first prime minister, as a gift for his services to the nation: stabilising its finances, keeping it at peace and securing the Hanoverian succession.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Walpole did not accept the gift for himself.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He proposed – and the King agreed – that the Crown give the properties to the Office of First Lord of the Treasury.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Walpole would live there as the incumbent First Lord, but would vacate it for the next one.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To enlarge the new house, Walpole persuaded one *Mr.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Chicken*, the tenant of a cottage next door, to move to another house in Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This small house and the mansion at the back were then incorporated into Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Walpole commissioned William Kent to convert them into one building.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Kent joined the larger houses by building a two-storey structure between them, consisting of one long room on the ground floor and several above.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The remaining interior space was converted into a courtyard.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He connected the Downing Street houses with a corridor.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Having united the structures, Kent gutted and rebuilt the interior.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He then surmounted the third storey of the house at the back with a pediment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To allow Walpole quicker access to Parliament, Kent closed the north side entrance from St James's Park, and made the door in Downing Street the main entrance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] On 23 September 1735, the *London Daily Post* announced that: "Yesterday the Right Hon.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Sir Robert Walpole, with his Lady and Family, removed from their House in St James's Square, to his new House, adjoining to the Treasury in St James's Park".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Originally estimated at £8,000, the final cost probably exceeded £20,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Walpole did not enter through the now-famous door; that would not be installed until forty years later.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Kent's door was modest, belying the spacious elegance beyond.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The First Lord's new, albeit temporary, home had sixty rooms, with hardwood and marble floors, cornices, elegant pillars and marble mantelpieces; those on the west side with views of St James's Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] One of the largest rooms was a study measuring forty feet by twenty with enormous windows overlooking St James's Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] "My Lord's Study" (as Kent labelled it in his drawings) would later become the Cabinet Room where prime ministers meet with the Cabinet ministers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Shortly after moving in, Walpole ordered that a portion of the land outside his study be converted into a terrace and garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The same document confirmed that Number 10 Downing Street was: "meant to be annexed & united to the Office of his Majesty's Treasury & to be & to remain for the Use & Habitation of the first Commissioner of his Majesty's Treasury for the time being".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] At about the same time that William Kent was combining the Downing Street townhouse with the house at the back, he was also commissioned to design and construct a new Treasury building on the site of the old Tudor Cockpit located behind Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This project was completed in 1737 and included corridors connecting the Treasury building with 10 Downing Street allowing Walpole, as Chancellor of the Exchequer as well as First Lord of the Treasury, direct and convenient access to the Treasury offices.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In effect the Treasury building became an annex of 10 Downing Street and its staff worked directly for Walpole on treasury, patronage and other public business.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This arrangement remained in effect until the middle of the 19th century and until then all prime ministers who were also Chancellor took advantage of it.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] After Prime Minister Robert Peel "gave up" being Chancellor in 1841, and this separation of positions gradually became a convention of the constitution, a locked door was installed between the buildings limiting the Prime Minister's access to the Treasury and its staff.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Due to bomb damage in 1940, the Treasury relocated to the Government Offices Great George Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Then in 1963 the Cabinet Office (including the Prime Minister's Office) and later the Civil Service (with the Prime minister as Minister for the Civil Service) moved into the renovated Kent Treasury Building.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] "Under (Prime Minister) Blair . . . the locked door, symbolically and physically dividing No.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Although he had accepted it on behalf of future First Lords of the Treasury, it would be 21 years before any of his successors chose to live there; the five who followed Walpole preferred their own homes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This was the pattern until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Of the 31 First Lords from 1735 to 1902, only 16 (including Walpole) lived in Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] One reason many First Lords chose not to live in Number 10 was that most of them owned London town houses that were superior in size and quality.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Their possession of the house, albeit temporary, was a perquisite they could bestow as a political reward.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Most lent it to the Chancellor of the Exchequer, others to lesser officials or to friends and relatives.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Another reason for its unpopularity was that Number 10 was a hazardous place in which to live; it was prone to sinking because it was built on soft soil and a shallow foundation, and its floors buckled and walls and chimneys cracked.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It became unsafe and frequently required repairs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1766, for example, Charles Townshend, Chancellor of the Exchequer, pointed out that the house was in a dilapidated condition.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] His architect's letter to the Treasury stated: "...we have caused the House in Downing Street belonging to the Treasury to be surveyed, & find the Walls of the old part of the said House next the street to be much decayed, the Floors & Chimneys much sunk from the level".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Townshend ordered extensive repairs, which were still incomplete eight years later.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A note from Lord North to the Office of Works, dated September 1774, asks for the work on the front of the house, "which was begun by a Warrant from the Treasury dated 9 August 1766", to be finished.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Treasury officials complained that the building was costing too much to maintain; some suggested that it should be razed and a new house constructed on the site or elsewhere.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1782 the Board of Works reporting on "the dangerous state of the old part of the House", stated that "no time be lost in taking down said building".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1783 the Duke of Portland moved out because it was once again in need of repair.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A committee found that the money spent so far was insufficient.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This time the Board of Works declared that "the Repairs, Alterations & Additions at the Chancellor of the Exchequer's House will amount to the sum of £5,580, exclusive of the sum for which they already have His Majesty's Warrant.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] And praying a Warrant for the said sum of £5,580 – and also praying an Imprest of that sum to enable them to pay the Workmen".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This proved to be a gross underestimate; the final bill was over £11,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A few prime ministers however did enjoy living in Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Lord North, who conducted the war against the American Revolution, lived there happily with his family from 1767 to 1782.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] William Pitt the Younger, who made it his home for twenty years (longer than any First Lord before or since) from 1783 to 1801 and from 1804 to 1806, referred to it as "My vast, awkward house".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] While there, Pitt reduced the national debt, formed the Triple Alliance against France and won passage of the Act of Union that created the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Robinson, 1st Viscount Goderich, took a special liking to the house in the late 1820s and spent state funds lavishly remodelling the interior.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Nevertheless, for 70 years following Pitt's death in 1806, Number 10 was rarely used as the First Lord's residence.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] From 1834 to 1877, it was either vacant or used only for offices and meetings.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Downing Street declined at the turn of the 19th century, becoming surrounded with run-down buildings, dark alleys, the scene of crime and prostitution.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Earlier, the government had taken over the other Downing Street houses: the Colonial Office occupied Number 14 in 1798; the Foreign Office was at Number 16 and the houses on either side; the West India Department was in Number 18; and the Tithe Commissioners in Number 20.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The houses deteriorated from neglect, became unsafe, and one by one were demolished.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] By 1857 Downing Street's townhouses were all gone except for Number 10, Number 11 (customarily the Chancellor of the Exchequer's residence), and Number 12 (used as offices for Government Whips).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1879 a fire destroyed the upper floors of Number 12; it was renovated but only as a single-storey structure.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When Lord Salisbury retired in 1902, his nephew, Arthur James Balfour, became prime minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It was an easy transition: he was already First Lord of the Treasury and he was already living in Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Balfour revived the custom that Number 10 is the First Lord and Prime Minister's official residence.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Without a bomb shelter, during World War II the Prime Minister abandoned Number 10 instead using a flat in the Foreign office that became known as the No.10 Annexe, and lay above the much more comprehensive underground bunker used by Winston Churchill and now known as the Churchill War Rooms.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To reassure the people that his government was functioning normally, he insisted on being seen entering and leaving Number 10 occasionally, and indeed, continued to use it for meetings and dinners despite being urged not to.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Harold Wilson, during his second ministry from 1974 to 1976, lived in his home in Lord North Street because Mary Wilson wanted "a proper home".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Despite these exceptions, Number 10 has been known as the prime minister's official home for over one hundred years.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] By the turn of the 20th century, photography and the penny press had linked Number 10 in the public mind with the premiership.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The introduction of films and television would strengthen this association.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Pictures of prime ministers with distinguished guests at the door became commonplace.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] With or without the prime minister present, visitors had their picture taken.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Suffragettes posed in front of the door when they petitioned H.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Asquith for women's rights in 1913, a picture that became famous and was circulated around the world.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1931, Mahatma Gandhi, wearing a traditional homespun *dhoti*, posed leaving Number 10 after meeting with Ramsay MacDonald to discuss India's independence.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This picture, too, became famous, especially in India.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The freedom fighters could see their leader had been received in the prime minister's home.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Couse's elegant, understated door – stark black, framed in cream white with a bold white "10" clearly visible – was the perfect backdrop to record such events.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Prime Ministers made historic announcements from the front step.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Waving the Anglo-German Agreement of Friendship, Neville Chamberlain proclaimed "Peace with honour" in 1938 from Number 10 after his meeting with Adolf Hitler in Munich.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] During World War II, Churchill was photographed many times emerging confidently from Number 10 holding up two fingers in the sign for "Victory".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The building itself, however, did not escape the London Blitz entirely unscathed; in February 1944 a bomb fell on nearby Horse Guards Parade and some of the drawing-room windows were destroyed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The symbol of British government, Number 10 became a gathering place for protesters.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Emmeline Pankhurst and other suffragette leaders stormed Downing Street in 1908; anti-Vietnam War protestors marched there in the 1960s, as did anti-Iraq War protestors in 2005.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] By the middle of the 20th century, Number 10 was falling apart again.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The deterioration had been obvious for some time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The number of people allowed in the upper floors was limited for fear the bearing walls would collapse.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The staircase had sunk several inches; some steps were buckled and the balustrade was out of alignment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The interior wood in the Cabinet Room's double columns was like sawdust.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Skirting boards, doors, sills and other woodwork were riddled and weakened with disease.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] After reconstruction had begun, miners dug down into the foundations and found that the huge wooden beams supporting the house had decayed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1958, a committee under the chairmanship of the Earl of Crawford and Balcarres was appointed by Harold Macmillan to investigate the condition of the house and make recommendations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The interior would be photographed, measured, disassembled, and restored.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A new foundation with deep piles would be laid and the original buildings reassembled on top of it, allowing for much needed expansion and modernisation.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Any original materials that were beyond repair – such as the pair of double columns in the Cabinet Room – would be replicated in detail.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This was a formidable undertaking: the three buildings contained over 200 rooms spread out over five floors.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The architect Raymond Erith carried out the design for this painstaking work and the contractor that undertook it was John Mowlem & Co.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] *The Times* reported initially that the cost for the project would be £400,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] After more careful studies were completed, it was concluded that the "total cost was likely to be £1,250,000" and the work would take two years to complete.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In the end, the cost was close to £3,000,000 and the work took almost three years due in large part to 14 labour strikes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] There were also delays when archaeological excavations uncovered important artefacts dating from Roman, Saxon and medieval times.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Macmillan lived in Admiralty House during the reconstruction.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The new foundation was made of steel-reinforced concrete with pilings sunk 6 to 18 feet (1.8 to 5.5 m).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The "new" Number 10 consisted of about 60% new materials; the remaining 40% was either restored or replicas of originals.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Many rooms and sections of the new building were reconstructed exactly as they were in the old Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] These included: the garden floor, the door and entrance foyer, the stairway, the hallway to the Cabinet Room, the Cabinet Room, the garden and terrace, the Small and Large State Rooms and the three reception rooms.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The staircase, however, was rebuilt and simplified.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Steel was hidden inside the columns in the Pillared Drawing Room to support the floor above.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The upper floors were modernised and the third floor extended over Numbers 11 and 12 to allow more living space.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] As many as 40 coats of paint were stripped from the elaborate cornices in the main rooms revealing details unseen for almost 200 years in some cases.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When builders examined the exterior façade, they discovered that the black colour visible even in photographs from the mid-19th century was misleading; the bricks were actually yellow.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The black appearance was the product of two centuries of pollution.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To preserve the 'traditional' look of recent times, the newly cleaned yellow bricks were painted black to resemble their well-known appearance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Although the reconstruction was generally considered an architectural triumph, Erith was disappointed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He complained openly during and after the project that the government had altered his design to save money.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] "I am heart broken by the result," he said.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] "The whole project has been a frightful waste of money because it just has not been done properly.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Ministry of Works has insisted on economy after economy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] I am bitterly disappointed with what has happened." Erith described the numbers on the front, intended to be based on historical models, as 'a mess' and 'completely wrong' to a fellow historian.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Within a few years, dry rot was discovered, especially in the main rooms due to inadequate waterproofing and a broken water pipe.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Extensive reconstruction again had to be undertaken in the late 1960s to resolve these problems.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Further extensive repairs and remodelling, commissioned by Margaret Thatcher, were completed in the 1980s under the direction of Erith's associate Quinlan Terry.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The work done by Erith and Terry in the 1960s and 1980s represents the most extensive remodelling of Number 10 in recent times.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Since 1990 when the Terry reconstruction was completed, repairing, redecorating, remodelling, and updating the house has been ongoing as needed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The IRA mortar attack in February 1991 led to extensive work being done to repair the damage (mostly to the garden and exterior walls) and to improve security.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In the summer of 1993 windows were rebuilt and in 1995 computer cables installed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1997, the building was remodelled to provide extra space for the prime minister's greatly increased staff.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To accommodate their large families, both Tony Blair and David Cameron chose to live in the private residence above Number 11 rather than the smaller one above Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 2010, the Camerons completely modernised the 50-year-old private kitchen in Number 11.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In March 2020, Boris Johnson refurbished the residential apartment at Number 11.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This became the subject of public controversy, and an Electoral Commission inquiry took place into the financing of the refurbishment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In May 2023, a car was driven into the Downing Street gates.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Rishi Sunak was present inside the residences at the time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A man was arrested by police and the car crash was not terrorism-related.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The current prime minister is Keir Starmer.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street houses the Cabinet Room, in which Cabinet meetings take place, chaired by the prime minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It also houses the Prime Minister's Executive Office, which deals with government logistics and diplomacy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Number 10's door is the product of the renovations Charles Townshend ordered in 1766; it was probably not completed until 1772.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Executed in the Georgian style by the architect Kenton Couse, it is unassuming and narrow, consisting of a single white stone step leading to a modest brick front.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The small, six-panelled door, originally made of black oak, is surrounded by cream-coloured casing and adorned with a semicircular fanlight window.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Painted in white, between the top and middle sets of panels, is the number "10".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The zero of the number "10" is painted in a very eccentric style, in a 37° angle anticlockwise.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] One theory is that this is in fact a capital 'O' as found in the Trajan alphabet that was used by the Ministry of Works at the time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A black iron knocker in the shape of a lion's head is between the two middle panels; below the knocker is a brass letter box with the inscription "First Lord of the Treasury".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The doorbell is inscribed with "PUSH" although is rarely used in practice.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A black ironwork fence with spiked newel posts runs along the front of the house and up each side of the step to the door.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The fence rises above the step into a double-swirled archway, supporting an iron gas lamp surmounted by a crown.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In modern times the door cannot be opened from the outside; there is always someone inside to grant entry.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] After the IRA mortar attack in 1991, the original black oak door was replaced by a blast-proof steel one.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Regularly removed for refurbishment and replaced with a replica, it is so heavy that it takes eight men to lift it.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The brass letterbox still bears the legend "First Lord of the Treasury".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The original door was put on display in the Churchill Museum at the Cabinet War Rooms.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Beyond the door, Couse installed black and white marble tiles in the entrance hall that are still in use.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A guard's chair designed by Thomas Chippendale sits in one corner.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Once used when policemen sat on watch outside in the street, it has an unusual "hood" designed to protect them from the wind and cold and a drawer underneath where hot coals were placed to provide warmth.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Scratches on the right arm were caused by their pistols rubbing up against the leather.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Couse also added a bow front to the small cottage – formerly Mr Chicken's house – incorporated into Number 10 in Walpole's time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When William Kent rebuilt the interior between 1732 and 1734, his craftsmen created a stone triple staircase.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The main section had no visible supports.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] With a wrought iron balustrade, embellished with a scroll design, and mahogany handrail, it rises from the garden floor to the third floor.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Kent's staircase is the first architectural feature visitors see as they enter Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Black and white engravings and photographs of all the past prime ministers decorate the wall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] They are rearranged slightly to make room for a photograph of each new prime minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] There is one exception: Winston Churchill is represented in two photographs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] At the bottom of the staircase are group photographs of prime ministers with their Cabinet ministers and representatives to imperial conferences.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In Kent's design for the enlarged Number 10, the Cabinet Room was a simple rectangular space with enormous windows.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] As part of the renovations begun in 1783, it was extended, giving the space its modern appearance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Probably not completed until 1796, this alteration was achieved by removing the east wall and rebuilding it several feet inside the adjoining secretaries' room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] At the entrance, a screen of two pairs of Corinthian columns was erected (to carry the extra span of the ceiling) supporting a moulded entablature that wraps around the room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Robert Taylor, the architect who executed this concept, was knighted on its completion.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The resulting small space, framed by the pillars, serves as an anteroom to the larger area.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Hendrick Danckerts' painting "The Palace of Whitehall" usually hangs in the vestibule.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It also contains two large bookcases that house the prime minister's library; Cabinet members traditionally donate to the collection on leaving office – a tradition that began with Ramsay MacDonald in 1931.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Although Kent intended the First Lord to use this space as his study, it has rarely served that purpose; it has almost always been the Cabinet Room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Stanley Baldwin used the Cabinet Room as his office.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A few prime ministers, such as Tony Blair, occasionally worked at the Cabinet Room table.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Painted off-white with large floor to ceiling windows along one of the long walls, the room is light and airy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Three brass chandeliers hang from the high ceiling.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Cabinet table, purchased during the Gladstone era, dominates the room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The modern boat-shaped top, introduced by Harold Macmillan in the late 1950s, is supported by huge original oak legs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The table is surrounded by carved, solid mahogany chairs that also date from the Gladstone era.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The prime minister's chair, the only one with arms, is situated midway along one side in front of the marble fireplace, facing the windows; when not in use, it is positioned at an angle for easy access.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The only picture in the room is a copy of a portrait of Robert Walpole by Jean-Baptiste van Loo hanging over the fireplace.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Number 10 has three inter-linked state drawing rooms: the Pillared Drawing Room, the Terracotta Drawing Room and the White Drawing Room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The largest is the Pillared Room thought to have been created in 1796 by Taylor.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Measuring 37 feet (11 m) long by 28 feet (8.5 m) wide, it takes its name from the twin Ionic pilasters with straight pediments at one end.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Today, there is a portrait of Queen Elizabeth I over the fireplace; during the Thatcher, Major and Blair ministries, a portrait of William Pitt by Romney was hung there.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A Persian carpet covers almost the entire floor.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A copy of a 16th-century original now kept in the Victoria and Albert Museum, there is an inscription woven into it that reads: "I have no refuge in the world other than thy threshold.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] My head has no protection other than this porchway.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The work of a slave of the holy place, Maqsud of Kashan in the year 926" (the Islamic year corresponding to 1520).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In the restoration conducted in the late 1980s, Quinlan Terry restored the fireplace.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Executed in the Kentian style, the small Ionic pilasters in the over-mantel are miniature duplicates of the large Ionic pillars in the room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Ionic motif is also found in the door surrounds and panelling.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Sparsely furnished with a few chairs and sofas around the walls, the Pillared Room is usually used to receive guests before they go into the State Dining Room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] However, it is sometimes used for other purposes that require a large open space.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] International agreements have been signed in this room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Tony Blair entertained the England Rugby Union team in the Pillared Room after they won the World Cup in 2003.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] John Logie Baird gave Ramsay MacDonald a demonstration of his invention, the television, in this room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] After the Apollo 11 lunar landing in July 1969, Harold Wilson hosted a reception in the room for the astronauts Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins, in addition to the Cambridge scientist Francis Thomas Bacon, inventor of the alkaline fuel cell used to generate power for space capsules.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Terracotta Room is the middle of the three drawing rooms.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It was used as the dining room when Robert Walpole was prime minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The name changes according to the colour it is painted.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When Margaret Thatcher came to power it was the Blue Room; she had it re-decorated and renamed the Green Room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In the renovation of the 1980s, Quinlan Terry introduced large Doric order columns to this room in the door surrounds and designed a very large Palladian overmantel for the fireplace with small double Doric columns on each side with the royal arms above.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Terry also added an ornate gilded ceiling to give the rooms a more stately look.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Carved into the plasterwork above the door leading to the Pillared Room is a tribute to Margaret Thatcher: a straw-carrying 'thatcher'.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The White State Drawing room was, until the 1940s, for the private use of prime ministers and their spouses.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It was here that Edward Heath kept his grand piano.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It is often used as the backdrop for television interviews and is in regular use as a meeting room for Downing Street staff.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The room links through to the Terracotta Room next door.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In the reconstruction during the late 1980s, Quinlan Terry used Corinthian columns and added ornate Baroque-style central ceiling mouldings and corner mouldings of the four national flowers of the United Kingdom: rose (England), thistle (Scotland), daffodil (Wales) and shamrock (Northern Ireland).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When Frederick Robinson (later Lord Goderich), became Chancellor of the Exchequer in 1823, he decided to leave a personal legacy to the nation.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To this end, he employed John Soane, the distinguished architect who had designed the Bank of England and many other famous buildings, to build a State Dining Room for Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Begun in 1825 and completed in 1826 at a cost of £2,000, the result is a spacious room with oak panelling and reeded mouldings.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Accessed through the first floor, its vaulted, arched ceiling rises up through the next so that it actually occupies two floors.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Measuring 42 by 26 feet (12.8 by 7.9 m), it is the largest room in Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Soane was the guest of honour when the dining room was first used on 4 April 1826.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The room is usually furnished with a table surrounded by 20 reproduction Adam style chairs originally made for the British Embassy in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] For larger gatherings, a horseshoe-shaped table is brought in that will accommodate up to 65 guests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] On these occasions, the table is set with the Silver Trust Silver set given to Downing Street in the 1990s.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Above the fireplace, overlooking the room, is a massive portrait by John Shackleton of George II, the king who originally gave the building to the First Lord of the Treasury in 1732.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Celebrity chefs such as Nigella Lawson have cooked for Prime Ministers' guests using the small kitchen next door.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Entering through the Small Dining Room, Blair used this room for his monthly press conferences.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The great kitchen located in the basement was another part of the renovations begun in 1783, probably also under the direction of Robert Taylor.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Seldom seen by anyone other than staff, the space is two storeys high with a huge arched window and vaulted ceiling.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Traditionally, it has always had a chopping block work table in the centre that is 14 feet (4.3 m) long, 3 feet (0.91 m) wide and 5 inches (13 cm) thick.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Above Taylor's vaulted kitchen, between the Pillared Room and the State Dining room, Soane created a Smaller Dining Room (sometimes called the Breakfast Room) that still exists.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To build it, Soane removed the chimney from the kitchen to put a door in the room.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He then moved the chimney to the east side, running a Y-shaped split flue inside the walls up either side of one of the windows above.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The room therefore has a unique architectural feature: over the fireplace there is a window instead of the usual chimney breast.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] With its flat unadorned ceiling, simple mouldings and deep window seats, the Small Dining Room is intimate and comfortable.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Usually furnished with a mahogany table seating only eight, Prime Ministers have often used this room when dining with family or when entertaining special guests on more personal state occasions.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The terrace and garden were constructed in 1736 shortly after Walpole moved into Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The terrace, extending across the back, provides a full view of St James's Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The garden is dominated by a 0.5 acres (0.20 ha) open lawn which wraps around Numbers 10 and 11 in an L-shape.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] No longer "fitted with variety Walle fruit and diverse fruit trees" as it was in the 17th century, there is now a centrally located flower bed around a holly tree surrounded by seats.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Tubs of flowers line the steps from the terrace; around the walls are rose beds with flowering and evergreen shrubs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The terrace and garden have provided a casual setting for many gatherings of First Lords with foreign dignitaries, Cabinet ministers, guests, and staff.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Prime Minister Tony Blair, for example, hosted a farewell reception in 2007 for his staff on the terrace.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] John Major announced his 1995 resignation as leader of the Conservative Party in the garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Churchill called his secretaries the "garden girls" because their offices overlook the garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It was also the location of the first press conference announcing the Coalition Government between David Cameron's Conservatives and Nick Clegg's Liberal Democrats.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Number 10 is filled with fine paintings, sculptures, busts and furniture.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] About half belong to the Government Art Collection.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The remainder are on loan from private collectors and from public galleries such as the National Portrait Gallery, the Tate Gallery, the Victoria and Albert Museum and the National Gallery.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] About a dozen paintings are changed annually.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] More extensive changes occur when a new prime minister takes office and redecorates.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] These redecorations may reflect both individual taste as well as make a political statement.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Edward Heath borrowed French paintings from the National Gallery and was loaned two Renoirs from a private collector.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] When Margaret Thatcher arrived in 1979 she insisted that the artwork had to be British and that it celebrate "British achievers".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] As a former chemist, she took pleasure in devoting the Small Dining Room to a collection of portraits of British scientists, such as Joseph Priestley and Humphry Davy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] During the 1990s John Major converted the first floor anteroom into a small gallery of modern art, mostly British.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He also introduced several paintings by John Constable and J.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Turner, Britain's two best known 19th-century artists, and cricketing paintings by Archibald Stuart-Wortley including a portrait of one of England's most celebrated batsmen W.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In addition to outstanding artwork, Number 10 contains many exceptional pieces of furniture either owned by the house or on loan.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] One of the most striking and unusual is the already mentioned Chippendale hooded guard's chair that sits in a corner of the entrance hall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To its left is a long case clock by Benson of Whitehaven.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] A similar clock by Samuel Whichcote of London stands in the Cabinet anteroom.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The White State Drawing Room contains examples of Adam furniture.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Green State Drawing Room contains mostly Chippendale furniture including a card table that belonged to Clive of India and a mahogany desk that is thought to have belonged to William Pitt the Younger and used by him during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In addition to the large carpet previously described, the Pillared State Drawing Room also contains a marble-topped table by Kent.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The State Dining Room contains a mahogany sideboard by Adam.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Until the late 19th century, Prime Ministers were required to furnish Number 10 at their own expense with furniture, tableware, china, linens, curtains and decorations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This arrangement began to change in 1877 when Benjamin Disraeli took up residency.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He insisted that the Treasury should bear the cost of furnishings at least in the public areas.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The Treasury agreed and a complex accounting procedure was developed whereby the outgoing prime minister was required to pay for "wear and tear" on furnishings that had been purchased by the Treasury.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] This system was used until November 1897 when the Treasury assumed responsibility for purchasing and maintaining almost all of the furnishings in both the public and private areas except decorating the walls with art work.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In 1924 when Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald took office, he did not own nor have the means to buy an extensive art collection.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] He had the Government Art Collection loan pieces.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The arrangement became the standard practice.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] To celebrate, Thatcher hosted a grand dinner in the State Dining Room for her living predecessors: Harold Macmillan, Alec Douglas-Home, Harold Wilson, Edward Heath and James Callaghan.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Also in attendance were Elizabeth II and representatives of the families of every 20th-century Prime Minister since H.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Asquith, including Lady Olwen Carey Evans (daughter of David Lloyd George), Lady Leonora Howard (daughter of Stanley Baldwin), and Clarissa Avon (widow of Anthony Eden and niece of Winston Churchill).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] That same year, the Leisure Circle published Christopher Jones' book *No.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street, The Story of a House*.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] In the foreword, Thatcher described her feelings for Number 10: "How much I wish that the public ... could share with me the feeling of Britain's historic greatness which pervades every nook and cranny of this complicated and meandering old building ...
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] All Prime Ministers are intensely aware that, as tenants and stewards of No.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street, they have in their charge one of the most precious jewels in the nation's heritage".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] For most of its history, Number 10 was accessible to the public.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Early security consisted of two police officers: one stood guard outside the door; the other was stationed inside to open it.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Since the door had no keyhole, the inside officer depended upon the lone outside officer.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] During Thatcher's premiership, terrorist threats led to the implementation of a second level of security.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Despite the added measure, on 7 February 1991, the Provisional IRA used a van they parked in Whitehall to launch a mortar bomb at Number 10.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] It exploded in the back garden, while Prime Minister John Major was holding a Cabinet meeting.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] Major moved to Admiralty House while repairs were being completed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/10-downing-street] The attack led to the famous black door being replaced with a new blast-proof door and the addition of guardhouses at the street ends as well as other less visible measures to further improve security of Downing Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On 15 February 2003, a coordinated day of protests was held across the world in which people in more than 600 cities expressed opposition to the imminent Iraq War.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was part of a series of protests and political events that had begun in 2002 and continued as the invasion, war, and occupation took place.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The day was described by social movement researchers as "the largest protest event in human history".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to BBC News, between six and ten million people took part in protests in up to sixty countries over the weekend of 15 and 16 February.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in Europe.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The one in Rome involved around three million people, and is listed in the 2004 *Guinness Book of World Records* as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Madrid hosted the second largest rally with more than 1.5 million people protesting against the invasion of Iraq.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, three smaller protests were held the following day, attended by foreigners and domestic students.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2002, the United States government began to argue for the necessity of invading Iraq.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This formally began with a speech by US President George W.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bush to the United Nations General Assembly on 12 September 2002 which argued that the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein was violating United Nations (UN) resolutions, primarily on weapons of mass destruction, and that this necessitated action.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposed war was controversial with many people questioning the motives of the US government and its rationale.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One poll which covered 41 countries claimed that less than 10% would support an invasion of Iraq without UN sanction and that half would not support an invasion under any circumstances.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war groups worldwide organised public protests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the French academic Dominique Reynié, between 3 January and 12 April 2003, 36 million people across the globe took part in almost 3,000 anti‑war protests, the demonstrations on 15 February 2003 being the largest and most prolific.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The 15 February international protests were unprecedented not only in terms of the size of the demonstrations but also in terms of the international coordination involved.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Immanuel Wallerstein has spoken of the international protests as being organised by the forces of "the camps of Porto Alegre and Davos" in reference to the emergence of global social movements who had been organising around international events such as the 2001 World Social Forum in Porto Alegre.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The idea for an international day of demonstrations was first raised by the British anti-capitalist group Globalise Resistance (GR) in the wake of an anti-war demonstration in Britain of 400,000 on 28 September.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time GR was involved in planning for the Florence European Social Forum (ESF) and brought up the suggestion at an ESF planning meeting.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to GR's Chris Nineham, "There was considerable controversy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Some delegates were worried it would alienate the mainstream of the movement.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposal was accepted and at the final rally of the ESF, in November 2002, the call officially went out for Europe-wide demonstrations on 15 February 2003.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This call was firmed up in December at a planning meeting for the following ESF which took place in Copenhagen in 2003.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This meeting was attended by delegates from many European anti-war organisations, the US group United for Peace and Justice, and representatives of groups from the Philippines.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The decision was taken to set up a Europe-wide anti-war website and to commit to spreading organisational coordination both within and beyond Europe.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An email network connecting the different national organisations across Europe, and eventually also the different US groups, was set up.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In December 2002, the Cairo Anti-war Conference pledged to organize demonstrations in Egypt and the International Campaign Against Aggression on Iraq (which came out of the Cairo conference) sought to co-ordinate more demonstrations across the world.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around this time, the US anti-war group International ANSWER called for actions in North America supporting the proposed protests in Europe.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another important platform for the spreading call to demonstrate internationally occurred at the World Social Forum in Porto Alegre, Brazil which took place at the end of 2002.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] European delegates sought to popularize the plan for the increasingly international demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They met with some success, including the organisation of an anti‑war assembly which was attended by almost 1,000 people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The song "Boom!", by System of a Down, had a music video filmed on the day of the protest, showing the many protest locations and people's opinions on the Iraq War.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations took place across Europe and some of the largest drawing attendance figures in the tens of thousands in many cities.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately one-fifth of the total demonstrators worldwide protested in Europe.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austria, 30,000 people (SW estimate) took to the streets of its capital, Vienna.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Switzerland in order to "concentrate the movement" most activists agreed to organise a single demonstration for the whole country in Bern.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day roughly 40,000 people joined the protest in front of the Bundeshaus, the seat of the Swiss federal government and parliament.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration, which ran under the slogan **Nein zum Krieg gegen Irak – Kein Blut für Öl!** (No to war in Iraq – no blood for oil!) was the largest in Switzerland since 1945.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Slovenia, roughly 3,000 people gathered in Ljubljana's central park of Congress Square, supported by the mayor Danica Simšič, and marched the streets in one of the largest demonstrations since independence in 1991.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Benelux countries had large demonstrations for their total population size.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Belgium organisers had expected around 30,000 people to attend a demonstration in Brussels, which is the home of the European Parliament.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They were shocked by a turn out of approximately 100,000 people (WSWS and GLW estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march took over 3 hours to cross the city.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Netherlands saw around 70,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 75,000 people (WSWS estimate) protest in Amsterdam.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was the country's largest demonstration since the anti-nuclear campaigns of the 1980s.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti war website antiwar.com reports that 8,000-14,000 people were present at protests in Luxembourg, however they do not provide a citation for this figure.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bosnia and Herzegovina saw around 100 protesters gather in Mostar.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This protest spanned the sectarian divide with both Bosniaks and Croats attending.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in Croatia where 10,000 people (WSWS estimate) took part in a protest in the capital city of Zagreb.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Croatia also saw protests in Osijek, Vukovar, Knin, Zadar, Šibenik, Split and Dubrovnik.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Cyprus saw a demonstration of between 500 (*USA Today* estimate) and more than 800 people (SW estimate) at the British army base in Dhekelia.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Enduring heavy rain protesters briefly blocked the base.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They then marched to Pyla village where they watched other demonstrations occurring across the world on a giant screen.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was mostly attended by Greek Cypriots but they were joined by some Turkish Cypriots.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the Czech Republic, over 1,000 people joined a rally at Jan Palach Square in Prague.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Czech philosopher Erazim Kohak addressed the crowd, saying, "War is not a solution, war is a problem." Protesters listened to music and speeches before marching to the Czech government building, where they submitted petitions, then march continued to the US embassy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In France, there were demonstrations in somewhere between twenty (*Observer* estimate) and eighty cities (WSWS estimate); the organisers estimated that over half a million marched in total.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration took place in Paris, where around 100,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 200,000 (WSWS estimate) people marched through the streets, ending in a rally at the Place de la Bastille.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This location's role in the French Revolution was considered to give it a historical significance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Toulouse of around 10,000 people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Germany, coaches brought people from over 300 German towns to Berlin to join a demonstration of 300,000 (police estimate) to 500,000 (organizers' estimate) people; the largest demonstration that had occurred in Berlin for several decades.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters, including members of Gerhard Schröder's government, filled the boulevard between the Brandenburg Gate and the Victory Column.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Athens, Greece, 150,000 people (WSWS estimate) demonstrated.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was generally peaceful, but a small group clashed with police.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police fired tear gas at the group some of whom threw rocks and petrol bombs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police reported that the trouble was down to a group of anarchists who had split off from the main demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Ireland, the Dublin march was only expected to draw 20,000 people, but the actual figure was given variously as 80,000 (police estimate), 90,000 (BBC estimate), 100,000 (*Guardian* estimate) or 150,000 (Socialist Worker (SW) estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march went from Parnell Square, passing the Department of Foreign Affairs at St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Stephen's Green, and on to the Dame Street for a rally where popular Irish folk singer Christy Moore, Kíla and Labour Party politician Michael D.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Higgins were among many speakers from the platform.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march disrupted traffic for more than four hours.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters demanded that the Irish government stop allowing the United States military to use Ireland's Shannon Airport as a transatlantic stop-off point in bringing soldiers to the Middle East.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the global day of protest took place in Italy in Rome.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Nearly 3,000 buses and thirty trains were specially chartered to bring people to the demonstration, which was organised under the slogan "Stop the war; no ifs or buts".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The organisers were shocked at the size of the turn out and the unexpected number of people forced the demonstration to set off two hours early.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The size of the demonstration meant that the majority of demonstrators did not make it into the final rally and in total three million people (organisers' estimate, supported by the Guinness Book of World Records) were on the streets.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was listed in the 2004 Guinness Book of World Records as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the *Green Left Weekly* (GLW), the demonstration contained people from across Italian society; "Catholic nuns and priests marched alongside young people with dreadlocks, nose rings and Palestinian scarves.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Christians, anarchists and communists mingled".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately 1,000 demonstrated (SW estimate) in Malta.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] After the demonstration an anti-war concert was held in the capital, Valletta.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Norway saw its biggest series of protests since 1917.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in its capital Oslo were more than 60,000 protesters (Police estimate and Socialist Worker estimate) joining a demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of around 15,000 took place in Bergen and Trondheim, and 10,000 in Stavanger.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests also took place in at least 30 towns across the country.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the rally in Oslo the vice-chair of the Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions (LO) spoke from the platform claiming that "Bush only cares about American oil interests".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Denmark 20,000 to 30,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) took part in a march in the capital city, Copenhagen.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Sweden, 35,000 demonstrated in Stockholm. and about 25,000 in Gothenburg.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Helsinki, Finland, an estimated 15,000 people participated in one of the largest mass-protests in the republic's history.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was a demonstration in Warsaw, Poland of 10,000 people (SW estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration through central Warsaw passed the US embassy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another protest, organized by the local Wrocław Anti-War Coalition (WKA), was held in the city of Wrocław in the market square by the town hall, with 400–500 people participating.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lisbon, police estimated that around 35,000 people gathered to march through the city.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Three former Portuguese prime ministers were in attendance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Russia, which had several demonstrations, the largest occurred in Moscow, with 200,000 people (WSWS estimate) in attendance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small demonstrations also took place in Serbia, where there was a demonstration of 200 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Belgrade.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was estimated that 1,000 people marched in the capital of Slovakia, Bratislava.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Barcelona also had a large, with estimates of 350,000 (Delegación de Gobierno), 1,300,000 (Barcelona city hall and Police) or 1,500,000 (GLW) people joining a demonstration which moved from the Passeig de Gràcia to the Plaça de Tetuan.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The city of Oviedo had a population of 180,000 and a turnout of 100,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The main demonstration in Turkey took place in Istanbul, thousands (SW estimate) demonstrated.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The local authorities had banned the protest claiming to have worries about national security, however the protest organisers went ahead with the rally under the cover of calling a press conference.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations in Adana, Ankara, İzmir, Zonguldak, İzmit, Antalya and Muğla.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Ukraine of around 2,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a "Rock against the war" rally in Kyiv's central square.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the lead-up to 15 February, the Stop the War Coalition was organising the march from a small office donated by the National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They planned for the two marches to merge at Piccadilly Circus and then proceed to a rally at Hyde Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The negotiations for this plan faltered when the Labour government's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport Tessa Jowell initially instructed the Royal Parks agency to deny permission for the rally in Hyde Park for safety reasons and to protect the grass.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Trafalgar Square was suggested by Jowell as the alternative venue, but the Mayor of London Ken Livingstone insisted it was of insufficient size.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The government's decision was reversed by 5 February.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sections of the media supported this demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The *Daily Mirror* gave large coverage in the lead up to the march and provided thousands of placards on the day.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration also received sponsorship support from Greenpeace and Mecca-Cola.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As the date for the march approached the BBC was predicting that around 500,000 people would attend, while StWC was hoping for numbers to top the symbolically significant million mark.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The British Stop the War Coalition (Stop) claimed the protest in London was the largest political demonstration in the city's history.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police estimated attendance as well in excess of 750,000 people and the BBC estimated that around a million attended.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The weather, on the day of the protest was grey and cold, but reports noted that people remained "in high spirits" as London became gridlocked and protesters were stuck for hours at Gower Street and the Embankment, the two starting points for the march.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police began the march earlier than intended on safety grounds because of the number of people who had arrived in central London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Hundreds of coaches brought protesters from 250 towns and cities across the UK, with around 100 coaches coming from Wales alone.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many commentators noted the diversity of those attending the march.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] All police leave in the capital was cancelled for the event, though Scotland Yard later said that it passed off almost without incident.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters who managed to reach Hyde Park in time heard various speakers, including Harold Pinter, George Galloway, Tony Benn and Bianca Jagger however many were not able to reach the rally as those travelling home by coach had to leave before completing the march route.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters at the back end of the march did not reach Hyde Park until hours after the speakers and performers had finished.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Charles Kennedy, then the leader of the Liberal Democrats, was a late addition to the list of speakers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some media speculation that he only decided to speak after a lead article in *The Guardian* was critical of his absence from the planned speaker list.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Because of the size of the march, accurate estimates of the number of people in attendance are difficult.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It is relatively uncontentious that the march was the largest ever political demonstration in the UK and the biggest taking to the streets since the Golden Jubilee weekend in 2002.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In an ICM poll for *The Guardian* (14 February 2003 – 16 February 2003), 6% of people claimed that someone from their household went on the march or had intended to.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Stop claims that this translates into 1.25 million households and thus supports the estimate of two million people, assuming that more than one person could come from each household.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] RadioVague in conjunction with the now defunct CableRadio broadcast speeches, music and interviews from the event to the internet throughout the day using a satellite uplink provided by Psand.net.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A sole person demonstrated in opposition to the march outside the Iraqi section of the Jordanian Embassy on the day – Jacques More a writer from Croydon – with a placard saying that, although a last resort, war is necessary "[w]hen evil dictators rule and murder their own people".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Ten years on writer Ian Sinclair assembled an oral history of the demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Journalist Ellie Mae O'Hagan, a UK Uncut activist, told Sinclair that despite its size "it did absolutely nothing".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other witnesses, such as Milan Rai, are of the opposite opinion: "We achieved a lot, and a hell of a lot more than we realise".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tariq Ali, one of the speakers in February 2003, said at the tenth anniversary: "I didn't quite tell them 'Blair is going to go to war regardless of today' but I knew that".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "It was a huge show of anger but that's about it.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "One demonstration never overturned government policy overnight – or very rarely – and on something as strategic and massive as that", commented Seumas Milne in an interview with *The Quietus* online magazine in October 2012.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In addition to the demonstrations in England, the United Kingdom also saw protests in Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war activists planned a demonstration in Glasgow which ended at the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre (SECC) where the Labour Party was holding a conference for party members.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party requested that the SECC refuse permission for a stage and PA system outside the conference hall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In response to this the then Scottish Socialist Party MSP Tommy Sheridan tabled a motion in the Scottish Parliament to allow the event to take place, condemning what he claimed were attempts to "stifle all opposition to warmonger Blair".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party was unsuccessful in blocking the demonstrators' plans.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tony Blair was due to give a speech at the same time as the protesters would have arrived outside the conference centre, but the speech was rescheduled to an earlier time to avoid this.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day around 50,000 people according to the *Guardian* joined the march, which started at Glasgow Green.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the time the front of the march had travelled the 2 miles (3.2 km) to the SECC, Blair had delivered his speech and had left the area.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Northern Irish march was held in Belfast, where 10,000 (*Guardian* estimate) to 20,000 (SW estimate) protesters from across the sectarian divide joined the demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march started at the Arts College at 14:30 and moved through that Royal Avenue towards Belfast City Hall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Prominent politicians from Sinn Féin, the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and the centrist Alliance Party joined the protest.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sinn Féin president Gerry Adams spoke from the platform at the end rally saying "If President Bush and Mr Blair want war, it should be war against poverty and for equality." There was also a rally in Newry in County Down attending by hundreds of protesters (BBC estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Canada saw protests in 70 cities and towns (WSWS estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in Montreal where more than 100,000 people protested (SW and WSWS each estimated 150,000) despite windchill temperatures below −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 80,000 people joined a demonstration in Toronto, 40,000 in Vancouver, 18,000 (by police estimates) in Edmonton, 8,000 in Victoria, 4,000 in Halifax and 6,000 in Ottawa.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were protests in 70 cities in total.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] These demonstrations took place despite very cold weather, average temperatures were below −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Chicoutimi, 1,500 protested in windchill temperatures of −40 °C (−40 °F) wind-chill temperature in what was one of the coldest marches on that global day of protest.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place all across the United States of America with CBS reporting that 150 U.S. cities had protests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the World Socialist Web Site, protests took place in 225 different communities.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in the nation's largest cities including Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York City, but there were also smaller rallies in towns such as Gainesville, Georgia; Macomb, Illinois; and Juneau, Alaska, among scores of others.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Organisers of the New York City protest had hoped to march past the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a week before the march, police claimed that they would not be able to ensure order and District Court Judge Barbara Jones ruled against allowing the route.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Instead, protesters were only permitted to hold a stationary rally.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On that day, over 300 buses and four special trains brought protesters in from across the country.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] BBC estimates that 100,000 protesters took part in a rally near the UN headquarters.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among those taking part was the 9/11 Families For Peaceful Tomorrows, a group made up of some relatives of victims of the attacks on the World Trade Center.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Speakers included politicians, church leaders and entertainers, such as actress Susan Sarandon and South African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As people tried to reach the rally area they ended up constituting an unplanned march, stretching twenty blocks down First Avenue and overflowing onto Second and Third Avenue.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In total estimates range from 300,000 to 400,000 protesters (WSWS estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests were largely peaceful though a small group of protesters who were reported to have broken off from the main rally, caused damage to property in Union Square, and threw stones at police officers, which resulted in forty arrests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were numerous complaints that the New York City Police Department (NYPD) were too heavy-handed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many streets were blocked off and protesters reported feeling hemmed in and scared.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the end of the day, police reported that there had been roughly 275 arrests; organisers dispute this number, claiming that there were 348 arrests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, NYPD spokesman Michael O'Looney denied the charges claiming that the tape was "filled with special effects" and that it did not prove the police had not been provoked.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At a demonstration in Los Angeles, California, 50,000 (WSWS estimate) to 60,000 (GLW estimate) protesters (CNN said "thousands") marched down Hollywood Boulevard filling it for four blocks.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Amongst the protesters were the actors Martin Sheen and Mike Farrell and director Rob Reiner.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Martin Sheen, who at the time was playing a fictitious U.S. president in *The West Wing*, said that "None of us can stop this war ... there is only one guy that can do that and he lives in the White House".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other activists in California originally planned to hold a protest in San Francisco on the Saturday but they changed to the Sunday in order not to conflict with the city's Chinese New Year's parade.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was held on Sunday 16 February.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The BBC estimated the crowd size to be 150,000 people, while protest organisers and police agreed that the crowd count was 200,000 people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a *San Francisco Chronicle* photographic investigation estimated that the number in attendance at the peak period was closer to 65,000 people, although it did not state how many people were in attendance for the duration of the demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some controversy over Rabbi Michael Lerner not being selected as a speaker for the rally at the end of the demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Lerner claimed that he was not picked to speak for reasons of antisemitism due to his support for the existence of the Israeli state.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austin, Texas, 10,000 protestors marched down Congress Avenue from the state capitol building.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Colorado Springs, 4,000 protesters were dispersed with pepper spray, tear gas, stun guns and batons.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 34 were arrested on failure to disperse and other charges and at least two protesters had to have hospital treatment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Seattle, organisers aimed to have 20 to 30 thousand people join a march from Seattle Center following a giant blue planet, the emblem adopted by the march organisers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day 50,000 people (GLW estimate) turned out to protest under the dual slogan "Stop the war on Iraq; Stop the war on immigrants", more than on the Seattle protests against the WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations also took place in Philadelphia, where thousands (CNN estimate) joined a march to the Liberty Bell, and in Chicago, where 10,000 people demonstrated (GLW estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Florida a small number of protesters staged a naked protest on Palm Beach.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They initially had some problems getting permission for the action, but on the Thursday before, a U.S.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] District court ruled that the planned nude protest was legal at the public beach.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Most of the attendees had come from the four-day Mid-Winter Naturist Festival that was taking place at the same time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration of 900 people (*USA Today* estimate) on the island of Puerto Rico.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The chief demonstration in Mexico took place in Mexico City where around 10,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a demonstration which ended with a rally at a heavily guarded US embassy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among the demonstrators was Nobel Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchú.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place across South America including Uruguay, where their protest took place on 14 February.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An estimated 70,000 people marched down Montevideo's Avenida 18.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Brazil, a protest led by President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva was attended by 1,500 marchers (Police estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Buenos Aires, Argentina, an estimate of 50,000 protesters attended which included some veterans of the Falklands War of 1982.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Areas in Asia with large Muslim populations, in particular the countries of the West Asia, had the highest levels of opposition to the proposed Iraq war, however demonstrations in many of these countries were relatively small.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The reasons for this are complex, but one factor that is commonly cited is the suppression of protest movements by the conservative leaders of those countries.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Iraq, the country in which the war would take place, protesters marched down Palestine Street in Baghdad where several thousand Iraqis—many carrying Kalashnikov rifles—joined in the global protests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Unlike the vast majority of protests across the world the protest in Baghdad was also in support of the Baathist regime; it was called by Saddam Hussein as "World Anger Day".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters carried posters of Saddam and burned US flags.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A large protest also took place on the streets of Damascus in Syria, which borders Iraq.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters chanted anti-U.S. and anti-Israeli slogans while marching to the "People's Assembly" in a demonstration of between 10,000 (GLW estimate) to 200,000 protesters (CBS estimate and *USA Today* estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lebanon, 10,000 protesters (CBS, GLW estimate) took part in a demonstration in Beirut.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protest ended early when it rained heavily.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations of 5,000 people (GLW estimate) in Amman, Jordan.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Israel there was a demonstration in Tel Aviv of approximately 2,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 3,000 people (GLW and WSWS estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration contained both Arabs and Jews.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was organized by a wide range of organizations including the Communist Party of Israel, the National Democratic Assembly, the Arab Democratic Party, the Independent Media Center, the Alternative Information Center, Ta'ayush, the Gush Shalom movement, and the Organization for Democratic Action.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, it was boycotted by other left-wing groups, including Peace Now and Meretz.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was coordinated with a similar demonstration which took place in Ramallah.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests took place across Japan mostly being held outside US military bases.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the day took place in Shibuya, where 5,000 (SW estimate) people marched.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, there was a demonstration of 25,000 in Tokyo on Friday, the day before as well as smaller demonstrations in Osaka and other cities.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Tokyo protests contained Japanese veterans of World War II and survivors of the 1945 atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 3,000 people (SW estimate) joined an illegal demonstration in the Malaysian city of Kuala Lumpur despite police warnings that any participants in a protest would face stern action.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration ended at the US embassy at Jalan Tun Razak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Taiwan had a protest of more than 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Taipei under the slogan of "No Blood for Oil".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] India saw protests across the country including 10,000 (BBC estimate) in Calcutta.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Bangladesh 2,000 people joined a demonstration in Dhaka.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In South Korea, there was a demonstration of 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) which took place in the capital city Seoul.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest started with a rally at Marronnier Park after which there was a demonstration that ended in Jongmyo were the size of the protest increased in size to 3,000 people (WSWS estimate).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Jongmyo was surrounded by riot police who almost out numbered the protesters.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests also took place in the South Korean cities of Busan, Daegu, Daejeon, Gwangju and Wonju.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, China, three protests were held the following day, attended by about 450 people in total, including foreigners and domestic students.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Johannesburg, around 8,000-10,000 people joined in a colorful and peaceful protest.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They toyi-toyied and marched, stopping at the U.S.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Consulate General where riot police formed a protective chain around the entrance.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Cape Town 5,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 20,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) joined a demonstration march which started at 10 in the morning on Keizersgracht road and ended at the offices of the US consulate-general which was guarded by a ring of riot police, where there was a rally with speakers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests were organised by the Anti-War Coalition and the Stop the War campaign of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of thousands of people also took place at Durban and Bloemfontein.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A number of prominent ANC politicians attended marches.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the Cape Town rally the South African Minister, Pallo Jordan addressed the protesters saying; "We will stop the war.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A protest of around 3,000 (SW estimate) in the Tunisian city of Sfax was attacked by police who beat the protesters with batons and truncheons, injuring at least 20.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests in Fiji took place on the day before, on Friday morning, heralding the weekend of demonstrations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters handed floral Valentine's Day messages to the representatives of the US, British and Australian governments urging them to avoid the war.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Friday also saw protests in Melbourne, where around 150,000 people (BBC estimate) joined a demonstration.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the Saturday protests also took place in Australia's national capital (Canberra), with 20,000 protesters.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Sydney demonstration on Sunday 16 February included a feeder march of 10,000 trade unionists, with 200,000 (BBC estimate) to 250,000 (Sydney Morning Herald estimate) demonstrating in Sydney.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Across the six state capitals an estimated 600,000 demonstrated in cities around the country.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Beyond the capitals, many major cities and towns around Australia had protests.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At protests in Australia in Bellingen, New South Wales around 2,500 people (SW estimate) joined a rally at the towns sports ground.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As well as hearing from speakers, the demonstrators were entertained by a group of a cappella singers called 'The Bushbombs'.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The rally was about as large as the town's population.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The first actual demonstration of the day took place in New Zealand where 10,000 people demonstrated in Auckland and Wellington.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Auckland march was bigger than expected, forcing police to shut off Queen Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] People were reported to be still starting the march as those at the front of the march reached a rally in Myers Park several kilometres away.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Wellington the march had to carry on after the then planned end point as there were too many people to fit into the park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 400 to 500 people marched in Hamilton.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in at least 18 other centres, including Dunedin, Thames, Opotiki, Whakatane, Whangarei, Timaru and Rotorua, and Picnic for Peace in Christchurch.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A group of scientists at the US McMurdo Station held a rally on the ice at the edge of the Ross Sea.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time, many commentators were hopeful that this global mobilization of unprecedented scale would stop the coming Iraq war.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] *The New York Times* writer Patrick Tyler claimed that they showed that there were "two superpowers on the planet – the United States, and worldwide public opinion".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The unprecedented size of the demonstrations was widely taken to indicate that the majority of people across the world opposed the war.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the potential effect of the protests was generally dismissed by pro-war politicians.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Her view was borne out as the day of protests, along with the protests that followed it, failed to stop the war.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protests and other public opposition were seen as a key factor in the decisions of the governments of many countries, such as Canada, to not send troops to Iraq, and of Turkey to deny coalition use of airbases in its territory.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests have also been cited as a factor strengthening the hand of the "uncommitted six" members of the United Nations Security Council - Angola, Cameroon, Chile, Mexico, and Pakistan.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Though demonstrations against the Iraq war and subsequent occupation continued, none of the demonstrations through to 2011 matched the 15 February protest in terms of size.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One suggested explanation for this is that people became disillusioned with marching as a political tactic because of the failure of these demonstrations to achieve their explicit aim.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2006, three years after the protest day, in an article arguing for people to attend a further march, Mike Marqusee put forward two counter arguments to this.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Firstly, he claimed that it was too soon to judge the long-term significance of the demonstrations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As examples, he stated, "People who took part in the non-cooperation campaigns in India in the 20s and 30s had to wait a long time for independence," and "There were eight years of protest and more than 2 million dead before the Vietnam war came to an end".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Secondly, he claimed that while the effect of marching may be uncertain, the effect of not marching would make it more likely that the occupation would continue.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Despite failing in its explicit aim, the 15 February global day of anti-war protests had many effects that, according to some, were not directly intended.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to United Kingdom left-wing anti-war activist Salma Yaqoob, one of these was that they were a powerful antidote to the idea that the war was a "Clash of Civilizations", or a religious war, an idea she claimed was propagated both by Western leaders and reactionary forces in the Arab world.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This is echoed in the words of former Hizb ut-Tahrir organiser Hadiya Masieh who said of the non-Muslims marching in London "How could we demonise people who obviously opposed aggression against Muslims?".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A severe outbreak of cholera occurred in 1854 near Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) and Golden Square in Soho, London, England, during the worldwide 1846–1860 cholera pandemic.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The outbreak (also known as **Golden Square outbreak**), which killed 616 people, is best known for the physician John Snow's study of its causes and his hypothesis that germ-contaminated water was the cause, rather than something in the air called "miasma".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This discovery influenced public health and the construction of improved sanitation facilities beginning in the mid-19th century.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Later, the term "focus of infection" was used to describe sites, such as the Broad Street pump, where conditions are favourable for transmission of infection.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow unknowingly took advantage of a natural experiment during his endeavours to identify the cause of cholera transmission.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In the mid-19th century, Soho in London had a serious problem with filth due to a large influx of people and lack of proper sanitary services: the London sewer system had not reached Soho.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cowsheds, slaughterhouses and grease-boiling dens lined the streets and contributed animal droppings, rotting fluids and other contaminants to Soho's primitive sewer system.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many cellars had cesspools beneath their floorboards, which formed from the sewers and filth seeping in from outside.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] With the cesspools overrunning, London's government decided to dump the waste into the River Thames, contaminating the water supply.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] London had already had a "series of debilitating cholera outbreaks".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] These included outbreaks in 1832 and 1849, which killed 14,137 people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time of the Broad Street outbreak, physicians and scientists held two competing theories on the causes of cholera in the human body: miasma theory and germ theory.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London medical community debated the cause of the city's persistent cholera outbreaks.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera-causing bacterium *Vibrio cholerae* was isolated in 1854, but the finding became well known and accepted only decades later.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists concluded that cholera was caused by particles in the air, or "miasmata", which arose from decomposing matter or other dirty organic sources.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "Miasma" particles were thought to travel through the air and infect individuals, and thus cause cholera.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr William Farr, the commissioner for the 1851 London census and a member of the General Register's Office, believed that miasma arose from the soil surrounding the River Thames.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It contained decaying organic matter which contained miasmatic particles and was released into the London air.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists believed in "cleansing and scouring, rather than through the purer scientific approach of microbiology".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Farr later agreed with Snow's germ theory following Snow's publications.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In contrast, the germ theory held that the principal cause of cholera was a germ cell that had not yet been identified.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow theorised that this unknown germ was transmitted from person to person by individuals ingesting water.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] John Simon, a pathologist and London's lead medical officer, called Snow's germ theory "peculiar".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Even though Simon understood Snow's theory, he questioned its relation to the cause of cholera.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] On 31 August 1854, after several other outbreaks elsewhere in the city, there was a major outbreak of cholera in Soho.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Over the next three days, 127 people on or near Broad Street died.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the next week, three quarters of the residents had fled the area.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By 10 September, more than 500 people had died and the mortality rate was 12.8 per thousand inhabitants in some parts of the city.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By the end of the outbreak, 616 people had died.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many of the victims were taken to the Middlesex Hospital, where their treatment was superintended by Florence Nightingale, who briefly joined the hospital in early September in order to help with the outbreak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to a letter by Elizabeth Gaskell, Nightingale "was up night and day from Friday afternoon (Sept.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] 1) to Sunday afternoon, receiving the poor creatures (chiefly fallen women of that neighbourhood - they had it the worst) who were being constantly brought in - - undressing them - putting on turpentine stupes, et cetera, doing it herself to as many as she could manage".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By talking to local residents (with the help of Reverend Henry Whitehead), Snow identified the outbreak's source as the public water pump on Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) at Cambridge Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Although Snow's chemical and microscope examination of a sample of the water from this Broad Street pump water did not conclusively prove its danger, the patterns of illness and death among residents in Soho persuaded the St James parish authorities to disable the pump by removing its handle.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow later used a dot map to illustrate how cases of cholera occurred around this pump.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] His efforts to connect the incidence of cholera with potential geographic sources was based on what is now known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He mapped the individual water pumps and generated cells representing all the points on his map that were closest to each pump.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The section of Snow's map representing areas in the city where the closest available source of water was the Broad Street pump had the highest incidence of cholera.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] There was one significant anomaly: none of the workers in the nearby Broad Street brewery contracted cholera.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As they were given a daily allowance of beer, they did not consume water from the nearby well.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the brewing process, the wort (un-fermented beer) is boiled in part so that hops can be added.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This step killed the cholera bacteria in the water they used to brew with, making it safe to drink.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow showed that the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company was taking water from sewage-polluted sections of the Thames and delivering it to homes, resulting in an increased incidence of cholera among its customers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's study is part of the history of public health and health geography.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It is regarded as the founding event of epidemiology.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It was discovered later that this public well had been dug 3 feet (0.9 m) from an old cesspit that had begun to leak faecal bacteria.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Waste water from washing nappies used by a baby who had contracted cholera from another source drained into this cesspit.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Its opening was under a nearby house that had been rebuilt further away after a fire and a street widening.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time there were cesspits under most homes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Most families tried to have their raw sewage collected and dumped in the Thames to prevent their cesspit from filling faster than the sewage could decompose into the soil.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the same time, an investigation of cholera transmission was being conducted in Deptford.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Around 90 people died within a few days in that town, where the water was known to be clean, and there had been no previous outbreaks of cholera.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was informed that the water had recently turned impure.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Before using it, residents had to let it run until the sudsy, sewer-like water turned clear.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow, finding that the water the residents were using was no different from the usual water from their pump, determined that the outbreak must be caused by a leak in the pipes that allowed surrounding sewage and its contaminants to seep in to the water supply.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This was similar to the Broad Street outbreak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The incoming water was being contaminated by the increasing levels of sewage, coupled with lack of safe plumbing.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] After the cholera epidemic subsided, government officials replaced the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They had responded only to the urgent threat posed to the population, and afterwards they rejected Snow's theory.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] To accept his proposal would have meant indirectly accepting the oral-faecal method of transmission of disease, which was too unpleasant for most of the public to contemplate.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Broad Street outbreak was an effect rather than a cause of the epidemic.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's conclusions were not predominantly based on the Broad Street outbreak, as he noted that he hesitated to come to a conclusion based on a population that had predominantly fled the neighbourhood and redistributed itself.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He feared throwing off results of the study.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] From a mathematical perspective, Snow's innovation was focusing on death rates in areas served by two water companies that drew water from the Thames, rather than basing it on data from victims of the Broad Street pump (which drew water from a well).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work also led to a far greater health and safety impact than the removal of the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Deactivating the pump "hardly made a dent in the citywide cholera epidemic, which went on to claim nearly 3,000 lives".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was sceptical of the prevailing miasma theory, which held that diseases such as cholera or the Black Death were caused by pollution or a noxious form of "bad air".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The germ theory was not yet established (Louis Pasteur proposed it in 1861).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow did not understand the mechanism by which disease was transmitted, but the evidence led him to believe that it was not foul air.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Based on the pattern of illness among residents, he hypothesized that cholera was spread by an agent in contaminated water.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He first published his theory in 1849, in an essay titled "On the Mode of Communication of Cholera".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1855 he published a second edition, including a more elaborate investigation of the effect of the water supply in the 1854 Soho outbreak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera epidemic of 1849–1854 was also related to the water supplied by companies in London at the time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The main players were the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company and the Lambeth Waterworks Company.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Both provided water to their customers drawn from the Thames, which was highly contaminated with visible and invisible products and bacteria.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Arthur Hill Hassall examined the filtered water and found it contained animal hair, among other foul substances.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Other companies, such as the New River Company and Chelsea Waterworks Company, were observed to have better filtered water; few deaths occurred in the neighbourhoods they supplied.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They not only obtained their water from cleaner sources than the Thames, but filtered the water and treated it until there were no obvious contaminants.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As mentioned above, Snow is known for his influence on public health, which arose after his studies of the cholera epidemic.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In attempting to figure out who was receiving impure water in each neighbourhood, what is now known as a double-blind experiment fell right into his lap.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow went on to study the water contents from each home through a test performed on each sample.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In this way, it could be deduced from which supplier the home received its water.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that it was indeed impure water from the big companies that allowed cholera to spread rapidly.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He proved this by observing London prisons, finding that cholera ceased there only a few days after switching to cleaner water sources.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's analysis of cholera and cholera outbreaks extended past the closure of the Broad Street pump.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that cholera was transmitted through and affected the alimentary canal within the human body.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cholera did not affect either the circulatory or the nervous system and there was no "poison in the blood...in the consecutive fever...the blood became poisoned from urea getting into the circulation".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, this "urea" entered the blood through kidney failure.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Therefore, the fever was caused by kidney failure, not by a poison already present in the subject's bloodstream.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Popular medical practices, such as bloodletting, could not be effective in such a case.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow also argued that cholera was not a product of Miasma.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "There was nothing in the air to account for the spread of cholera".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, cholera was spread by persons ingesting a substance, not through atmospheric transmittal.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Reverend Henry Whitehead was an assistant curate at St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Luke's church in Soho during the 1854 cholera outbreak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A former believer in the miasma theory of disease, Whitehead worked to disprove false theories.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was influenced by Snow's theory that cholera spreads by consumption of water contaminated by human waste.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work, particularly his maps of the Soho area cholera victims, convinced Whitehead that the Broad Street pump was the source of the local infections.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead joined Snow in tracking the contamination to a faulty cesspool and the outbreak's index case (the baby with cholera).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead's work with Snow combined demographic study with scientific observation, setting an important precedent for epidemiology.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London Board of Health, which had recently been given new powers and was presided over by Sir Benjamin Hall, a Cabinet Minister, had several committees, of which the Committee for Scientific Inquiries was placed in charge of investigating the cholera outbreak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They were to study the atmospheric environment in London and to examine samples of water from several London water companies.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The committee found that the most contaminated water supply came from the South London water companies, Southwark and Vauxhall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of the Committee for Scientific Inquiries, Richard Dundas Thomson and Arthur Hill Hassall examined what Thomson called "vibriones".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Thomson examined the occurrence of vibriones in air samples from various cholera wards and Hassall observed vibriones in water samples.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Neither identified vibriones as the cause of cholera.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of its investigation of the cholera epidemic, the Board of Health sent physicians to examine in detail the conditions of the Golden Square neighbourhood and its inhabitants.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Board of Health ultimately attributed the 1854 epidemic to miasma.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Edwin Lankester was a physician on the local research conglomerate that studied the 1854 Broad Street cholera epidemic.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1866, Lankester wrote about Snow's conclusion that the pump caused the outbreak.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He agreed with Snow at the time, but his opinion, like Snow's, was not publicly supported.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Lankester subsequently closed the pump due to Snow's theory and data on the pattern of infection, and infection rates dropped significantly.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was eventually named the first medical officer of health for St James's parish in London, the area where the pump was.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A replica pump was installed in 1992 at the site of the 1854 pump.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Every year the John Snow Society holds "Pumphandle Lectures" on public health subjects.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Until 2015, when the pump was removed due to redevelopment, it also held a ceremony there in which it removed and reattached the pump handle to commemorate Snow's discovery.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The pump's original location is marked by a red granite paver, and plaques at the John Snow pub at the corner describe Snow's findings.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 1872 association football match between the national teams of Scotland and England is officially recognised by FIFA as the first international.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It took place on 30 November 1872 at Hamilton Crescent, the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground in Partick, Glasgow.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was watched by 4,000 spectators and finished as a 0–0 draw.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Following public challenges issued in Glasgow and Edinburgh newspapers by The Football Association (FA) secretary Charles Alcock, the first encounter of five matches between teams representing England and Scotland took place in London on 5 March 1870 at The Oval, resulting in a 1–1 draw.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The second match was played on 19 November 1870, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] This was followed by matches on 25 February 1871, England 1–1 Scotland; 18 November 1871, England 2–1 Scotland; and 24 February 1872, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Most players selected for the Scottish side in these early "internationals" were from the London area, although players based in Scotland were also invited.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The only player affiliated to a Scottish club was Robert Smith of Queen's Park, Glasgow, who played in the November 1870 match and both of the 1871 games.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Robert Smith and James Smith (both of the Queen's Park club) were listed publicly for the February 1872 game, but neither played in the match.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] After the 1870 matches, there was resentment in Scotland that their team did not contain more players based in Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Alcock then proceeded to offer another challenge with a Scottish team drawn from Scotland and proposed the north of England as a venue.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] He appeared to be particularly concerned about the number of players in Scottish football teams at the time, adding: "More than eleven we do not care to play as it is with greater numbers it is our opinion the game becomes less scientific and more a trial of charging and brute force ...
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Charles W Alcock, Hon Sec of Football Association and Captain of English Eleven".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] One reason for the absence of a formal response to Alcock's challenge may have been different football codes being followed in Scotland at the time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] A written reply to Alcock's letter above states: "Mr Alcock's challenge to meet a Scotch eleven on the borders sounds very well and is doubtless well meant.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] But it may not be generally well known that Mr Alcock is a very leading supporter of what is called the 'association game' ... devotees of the 'association' rules will find no foemen worthy of their steel in Scotland".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Despite this the FA were hoping to play in Scotland as early as February 1872.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In 1872, Queen's Park, as Scotland's leading club, took up Alcock's challenge, despite there being no Scottish Football Association to sanction it.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In the FA's minutes of 3 October 1872 it was noted "In order to further the interests of the Association in Scotland, it was decided that during the current season, a team should be sent to Glasgow to play a match v Scotland".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was arranged for 30 November (St Andrew's Day), and the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground at Hamilton Crescent in Partick was selected as the venue.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] All eleven Scottish players were members of the Queen's Park, the leading Scottish club at this time, although three players were also members of other clubs; William Ker of Granville F.C. and the Smith brothers of South Norwood F.C.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland had hoped to obtain the services of Arthur Kinnaird of The Wanderers and Henry Renny-Tailyour of Royal Engineers but both were unavailable.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The teams for this match were gathered together "with some difficulty, each side losing some of their best men almost at the last moment".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scottish side was selected by goalkeeper and captain Robert Gardner.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English side was selected by Charles Alcock and contained players from nine clubs; Alcock himself was unable to play due to injury.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match, initially scheduled for 2pm, was delayed for 20 minutes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 4,000 spectators paid an entry fee of a shilling, the same amount charged at the 1872 FA Cup Final.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English wore caps, while the Scots wore red cowls.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match itself illustrated the advantage gained by the Queen's Park players "through knowing each others' play" as all came from the same club.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] There is no evidence in the article that the author attended the match, as the reader is clearly pointed to match descriptions in "sporting journals".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It is also of note that the 5 March 1872 match between Wanderers and Queen's Park contains no evidence of ball passing.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] At half-time, both teams rotated the goalkeeping duties among their players: England from Robert Barker to William Maynard, and Scotland from Gardner to Robert Smith.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] On a pitch that was heavy due to the continuous rain over the previous three days, the smaller and lighter Scottish side pushed their English counterparts hard.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots had a goal disallowed in the first half after the umpires decided that the ball had cleared the tape that was used to represent the crossbar.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The latter part of the match saw the Scots defence under pressure by the heavier English forwards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots played two full backs, two half backs and six forwards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English played only one full back, one half back and eight forwards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Since three defenders were required for a ball played to be onside, the English system was virtually a ready-made offside trap.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland came closest to winning the match when, in the closing stages, a Robert Leckie shot landed on top of the tape.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Though the match finished goalless, the quality of play was widely praised.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] "It was allowed to be the best game ever seen in Scotland" wrote the *Aberdeen Journal*.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The reports of the match that were published in the newspapers reveal further details of the 1872 Laws of the Game.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland won a defensive corner kick after England's attackers kicked the ball over the goal-line (a feature borrowed from Sheffield Rules but discarded in 1873).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The throw-in was awarded to the first team to touch the ball down after it went out of play (this too would be changed in 1873); and there was a break for half-time only because no goals had been scored in the first half.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The 18th century was a period of rapid growth for London, reflecting an increasing national population, the early stirrings of the Industrial Revolution, and London's role at the centre of the evolving British Empire.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] It saw immigrants and visitors from all over the world, particularly Huguenot migrants from France.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The built-up area of London increased dramatically in this period, particularly westward as areas such as Mayfair and Marylebone were constructed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Grand aristocratic mansions such as Spencer House were built, as well as churches such as St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Martin-in-the-Fields and Christ Church Spitalfields.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Crime such as armed robbery and sex work were particularly prevalent, leading to the development of early police forces such as the Bow Street Runners and the Thames River Police.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Capital and corporal punishment such as hanging, penal transportation and the pillory were used, but the period also saw the development of penitentiary prisons such as that at Coldbath Fields.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Londoners saw widespread violence during upheavals such as the Gordon Riots.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Many modern-day cultural institutions come from 18th century London, such as the Royal Society of Arts, the Royal Academy, the British Museum, the Royal Thames Yacht Club, Lord's Cricket Ground, *The Times*, *The Observer,* Theatre Royal Haymarket, and the Royal Opera House.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London-based artists and writers included Thomas Gainsborough, William Hogarth, Jonathan Swift, Mary Wollstonecraft, and Samuel Johnson.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London's economy was massively boosted by its shipping industry, but other important industries included silkweaving.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Many modern-day businesses trace their origins back to 18th-century London, including Sotheby's, WHSmith, and Schweppes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In order to transport goods and people, many new turnpikes and canals were constructed, and educational movements aimed at working-class children, such as Sunday schools, were pioneered in this period.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, about 500,000 people lived in London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] By 1713, this number had risen to 630,000; by 1760, it was 740,000, and by the end of the century, it was just over 1 million.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The average height of a male Londoner was 5 ft 7+1⁄4 in (171 cm) and the average height of a female Londoner was 5 ft 1+3⁄4 in (157 cm).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1768, the abolitionist Granville Sharp estimated that there were 20,000 Black people in domestic service in London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This included some who were enslaved, as evidenced by "for sale" or "runaway" notices in London newspapers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the aftermath of the American Revolutionary War in the 1780s, there was a small influx of Black Americans who had fought for the British and were therefore no longer welcome in the United States, many of whom become homeless.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Some Black Londoners became well known through their writings, such as Ignatius Sancho, Olaudah Equiano, Ottobah Cugoano, Robert Wedderburn, Ukawsaw Gronniosaw, Ayuba Suleiman Diallo, and Phillis Wheatley.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Other famous Black Londoners of the day include the violinist George Bridgetower, the fencing master Julius Soubise, and the aristocrats Dido Belle and William Ansah Sessarakoo.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Around the docks in the East End was a population of sailors from India and east Asia known as "lascars" employed on ships belonging to the East India Company.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The company ran a boarding house for them called Orchard House in Blackwall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the wealthier West End of London, Indians were more likely to be employed as domestic servants by officers and former officers of the East India Company.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1765, the *munshi* Mirza Sheikh I'tesamuddin became the first-known educated Indian to visit London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] He wrote a book in Persian on his experiences in Europe which was later translated into English by James Edward Alexander.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London had populations of immigrants from various European countries.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] After the rights of French Protestants called Huguenots were repealed in 1688, thousands fled to London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, there were an estimated 25,000 Huguenots in London, particularly in Soho and Spitalfields.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] At their height, there were 23 French churches in London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Successful Huguenots included the sculptor Louis François Roubiliac and the optician John Dollond.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] There was also a community of French Catholic immigrants, who ran French-language newspapers such as the *Courier Politique et Littéraire* and the *Courier de Londres*.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Well-known Londoners from other European countries include the painters Godfrey Kneller, and Johan Zoffany; and the sculptors Peter Scheemakers, Michael Rysbrack and Giuseppe Ceracchi.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1750, a population of the Bohemian Protestant sect called Moravians settled on Cheyne Walk in Chelsea.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] They established a Moravian church and burial ground.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] An estimated 30,000 Irish immigrants lived in London by the end of the period.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Some were particularly successful, including Robert Barker, Hans Sloane, James Barry, Charles Macklin, Jonathan Swift, Laurence Sterne, Oliver Goldsmith, and Richard Brinsley Sheridan.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Theoretically, Romani people and travellers had been expelled from England since the 1560s, but there was nonetheless a community in London in the 18th century, particularly in Norwood.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] They were particularly associated with horse dealing and fortune-telling at London's fairs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Well-known travellers of the period included Jacob Rewbrey of Westminster, Margaret Finch of Norwood, and Diana Boswell from Dulwich.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Historian Jerry White estimates that there were about 750 Jewish people living in London at the beginning of the period.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] By the end of the century, that number had risen to about 15,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1701, Bevis Marks synagogue opened to cater to Sephardic Jews descended from Spanish and Portuguese immigrants.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] It is still a working synagogue to this day.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Ashkenazi Jews, descended from Dutch, German and central European immigrants, used the Great Synagogue in Duke's Place, the Hambro' Synagogue off Fenchurch Street, and the New Synagogue on Leadenhall Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Practising Jews could not join the city's trade guilds, and so many Jewish business owners lived outside the city, in places like Aldgate and Whitechapel.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Michael Leoni was a famous Jewish singer, and Daniel Mendoza a famous Jewish boxer.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] There were smaller numbers of people who came from further afield, such as Mehemet von Königstreu and Ernst August Mustapha, Turkish valets to George I.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London also drew in people from all over the globe, even if they only visited for a short time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Examples include the Native American chief Tomochichi and his retinue, who met George II in 1734; the Raiatean man Mai, who visited in 1774 and had his portrait painted by the artist Joshua Reynolds; and the Aboriginal Australians Bennelong and Yemmerrawanne, who visited in 1793.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] A map of London made in 1700 (in black and white) compared to a map made in 1763 (in colour).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London has spread much further west in the second map, as far as Park Lane (marked as Tyburn Lane).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London's growth in the 18th century was marked above all by the westward shift of the population away from the City of London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Westminster was intensively developed, with new districts like Mayfair housing Britain's wealthiest aristocratic families.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Cavendish Square and Hanover Square were both laid out in the 1710s, while the Portman Estate, which occupies the western half of Marylebone, began its own building program in the 1750s with the granting of commercial leases, followed by the commencement of building on Portman Square in 1764.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Comparison of London maps made in the mid-17th century with ones made in the mid-18th century also reveal that the new developments were much more likely to be built along grid structures.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The most exclusive area, Mayfair, was intensively built up with luxury townhouses on an area occupied by seven different estates: the Grosvenor, Burlington, Berkeley, Curzon, Milfield, Conduit Mead, and Albemarle Ground estates.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Grosvenor estate, in the northwest corner between Oxford Street and Park Lane, was the most substantial private plot of land, featuring an orderly grid network of streets constructed around Grosvenor Square in the early 1720s.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] By 1738 "nearly the whole space between Piccadilly and Oxford Street was covered with buildings as far as Tyburn Lane [Park Lane], except in the south-western corner about Berkeley Square and Mayfair".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Further west, the Cadogan Estate began working on the area between Knightsbridge and Sloane Square in 1777.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] To the south, the area now known as Elephant & Castle was also laid out in this period, with a road from Westminster Bridge connecting up to Borough High Street, and the New Kent Road also constructed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] To the north, new developments sprang up around between Paddington and Islington such as Pentonville, named after its landlord, Henry Penton; and Somers Town, named after its landlord, Charles Cocks, 1st Baron Somers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Construction began on Bedford Square in 1775, which has been called "the most perfect of the London squares of the period", and Finsbury Square was begun in 1777.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Building started on Camden Town in 1791, named after the 1st Earl Camden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Rural villages surrounding Westminster and the city also grew in population and were gradually incorporated into the metropolis: areas like Bethnal Green and Shadwell to the east, or Paddington and St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1750 the London topographer John Noorthouck reckoned that London proper consisted of 46 former villages, two cities (Westminster and the City of London proper), and one borough (Southwark).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Buckingham House, later known as Buckingham Palace, was bought by George III in 1762.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1783, work began on expanding and renovating Carlton House for the then Prince of Wales, which took years to be completed as well as huge amounts of taxpayer money, only for the Prince to live there for a very short amount of time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 10 Downing Street was acquired by the Crown and offered to the Prime Minister Robert Walpole.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] As he already had many houses and didn't want to pay to upkeep another, he accepted it as a perk of his position, beginning the tradition of passing the house down to each successive Prime Minister.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] It was substantially remodelled by the architect William Kent.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The residence of the Lord Mayor of the City of London, Mansion House, was completed in 1753 after having been designed by architect George Dance the Elder.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The current Treasury building was completed in 1736.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Bevis Marks Synagogue was one of the first new religious buildings of the period, opening in 1701.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1710, the final stone was added to St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Paul's Cathedral, designed by Christopher Wren.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Paul's, which had been completely destroyed in the Great Fire of London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] A flurry of church-building between 1711 and 1730 also saw the construction of Christ Church Spitalfields, St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] John's Smith Square, and Grosvenor Chapel.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] After this, further churches built in the period include St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] George the Martyr, Southwark (1736), St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Another burst of church-building occurred towards the end of the period, with new churches such as St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The period also saw the construction of several bridges across the Thames alongside London Bridge.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] With the completion of Westminster Bridge in 1750, London gained a much needed second crossing onto the south bank, and Blackfriars Bridge opened in 1769.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] To the west, Putney Bridge was built in 1729, Kew built its first bridge in 1759, and Richmond Bridge opened in 1777.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The first Freemasons' Hall was built on Great Queen Street in 1776.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Severndroog Castle was built in 1784 to commemorate the seagoing victories of Sir William James, who had died the previous year.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Trinity House was built for the body that governs English and Welsh lighthouses in 1795.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Shop fronts also began to be built with large windows for passers-by to see the goods inside, examples of which can still be seen at 88 Dean Street and James Lock & Co on St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] New government offices included Somerset House, the Admiralty, and Horse Guards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] To accommodate the rapid growth of population, Parliament enacted building legislation and initiated important infrastructure projects.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Fleet River, which was so filled with rubbish and sewage that it had been a health hazard for many years, was finally covered over in 1733.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The New Road running between Paddington and Islington was constructed beginning in 1756.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Intended as a drover's road upon which livestock could be driven to Smithfield Market without encountering the congested road network of the city further south, the 60 ft (18 m) wide New Road was London's first bypass and served as the informal northern boundary for London for years to come.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The City Road was added in 1761, connecting the Angel to Finsbury Square.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] To improve traffic, the houses on London Bridge were removed in 1757, the Holbein Gate in Whitehall was removed in 1759, and the gates of the city were removed 1760–1777.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] A London building from the 17th century (in black and white) compared to one built in the 18th century (in colour).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Notice how the later building has no overhanging storeys or signs, and the window frames are recessed slightly.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] From 1707, buildings in London were no longer permitted with upper storeys overhanging the lower ones, so facades on future buildings were strictly vertical.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] After the Building Regulation Act 1709 (7 Ann. c.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 17), wooden window frames were required to be recessed at least 4 inches into the wall to prevent the spread of fire up a building's facade.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1762, shop signs that hung down were banned in the City and Westminster, and had to be fixed flat to the building instead to prevent them blocking out sunlight and falling on people walking underneath.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Building Act 1777 set building requirements for new housing and sought to eliminate rampant jerry-building and shoddy construction work.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Housing was divided into four "rates" based on ground rents, with each of the rates accorded their own strict building codes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Building Act accounts for the remarkable uniformity of Georgian terraced housing and squares in London built in subsequent decades, which critics like John Summerson criticized for their "inexpressible monotony".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Landmark legislation included the Westminster Paving Act 1765 (5 Geo.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 50), which required streets be equipped with pavements, drainage, and lighting.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The success of the legislation inspired the London Paving and Lighting Act 1766 (6 Geo.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 26), which extended the same provisions across the whole city and required that houses be numbered and streets and pavements be cleansed and swept regularly.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Street lighting was more extensive than in any other city in Europe, something which amazed foreign visitors to the capital in the late 18th century.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The practice of numbering houses also dates from this period, with some sources claiming it started in New Burlington Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The practice of putting street names on signs at each corner was taken up by the city from 1765 onwards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Armed robbery was particularly common in London, either by highwaymen (on horseback) or footpads (on foot).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One gang, run by a man called Obadiah Lemon, used fishing hooks to steal hats and wigs through open coach windows, or leapt on top and cut through the roof.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] George III himself was robbed of his shoe buckles and spare change while walking in Kensington Gardens.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] During the 1750s, several outyling towns in London's suburbs organised their own guard patrols to combat robbers on their roads.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] For example, Blackheath residents offered rewards for information on highwaymen in 1753, and Kentish Town inhabitants paid to hire guards in 1756.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Pickpocketing was also particularly common in London, where large crowds often gathered at executions and theatre performances.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] There was also large amounts of theft on the river, as ships laden with valuable goods waited with skeleton crews for a berth in the Pool of London. £70,000 worth of sugar alone was stolen per year from boats on the river.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Sex work was another common crime, particularly associated with Covent Garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1758, it was estimated that 3,000 sex workers lived in London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] On one routine sweep, constables arrested 22 sex workers in Covent Garden, two of whom were men dressed as women.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1757, a catalogue of London's sex workers was published called *Harris's List of Covent Garden Ladies*, which detailed the names, locations, and descriptions of hundreds of workers in the capital.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Although the crime of buggery was punishable by death, London had several establishments known as "molly houses", where queer men could meet.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] According to one homophobic pamphlet of the time, men in molly houses took on female personas and performed mock weddings and birth ceremonies.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The 18th century saw a huge backlash against molly houses, with the publication of pamphlets such as *The Sodomites' Shame and Doom*, and groups such as the Society for the Reformation of Manners attempting to track down queer men and have them prosecuted.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One of the most famous molly houses was Mother Clap's in Holborn, which was raided in 1726, resulting in 40 arrests and three hangings.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Mother Clap herself was sentenced to the pillory and two years in prison.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] There was no organised police force in this period.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In times of serious emergency, or in the case of organised gangs, the authorities could deploy the military, but this was deeply unpopular, both with citizens and with the military themselves.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] There were small, specialised forces, such as the King's Messengers (who dealt with sedition, particularly Jacobites), the Press Messengers (who dealt with seditious publishers) and the City Marshals (localised to the City of London).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Local magistrates, or Justices of the Peace, could issue warrants for criminals; and their officers, constables, would apprehend them.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Constables were also responsible for policing low-level criminals such as sex workers and fortune tellers, detecting crime, and raising the "hue and cry".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Below them, beadles were responsible for making sure that those who qualified for "outdoor relief" were receiving it, acting as town crier, and supervising the town watch; and the watch patrolled the streets at night armed with a lantern and a cudgel to discourage crime.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Corruption was endemic, meaning that if one wanted someone prosecuted, one had to do all the leg-work oneself, bribing officers at every stage.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In previous eras, Londoners had been able to claim sanctuary at monasteries and former monasteries in order to avoid the law, but by 1712 this practice had been eradicated.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Bow Street Magistrates' Court opened in 1740 in Covent Garden.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One of the magistrates, Henry Fielding, established the Bow Street Runners in 1749 as an early form of a police force.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] They took the form of six parish constables who acted as bounty hunters, being paid a regular salary plus bonuses for any criminal they apprehended who was successfully prosecuted.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Bow Street Runners were unusual in that they are generally agreed to have not been corrupt.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1754, John Fielding took over as chief magistrate, and his writings on the model popularised the concept across the country as he advocated for a national police force.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Fielding is even credited with popularising the word "police".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] By the end of the century, there were eight or nine other such groups belonging to magistrates' courts around London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Inspired by the Bow Street Runners, in 1798 Patrick Colquhoun set up the River Police, sometimes called the first professional police force in the country, which tackled crime in the docks and Pool of London.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Throughout the period, the number of crimes, especially property crimes, subject to the death penalty ballooned under a period of English law known as the Bloody Code.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Of those executions, London played host to the vast majority.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Hanging was a common punishment for several crimes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the period 1750–1775, 3.85 people per 100,000 were hanged per year on average, and only 12% of these were for murder, as the number of people executed for property crimes grew under the Bloody Code.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Hangings were public, and could attract large crowds depending on the fame of the victims.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] When the thief Jack Sheppard, who had escaped from prison multiple times, was finally hanged at Tyburn in 200,000 people reportedly came to see it.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the 1780s, the authorities stopped use of Tyburn as London's main execution site in favour of Newgate Prison.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The last person executed at Tyburn was a man called John Austin in 1782.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London employed a chief hangman and an assistant for this job, at a salary of £50 per year plus a guinea per execution.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The most famous of these was John Price, who was himself hanged for murder in 1718.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] As an extra punishment for particularly cold-blooded crimes, a hanged body would be publicly displayed in chains, such as a Mrs Phipoe in 1797, whose body was displayed at the Old Bailey.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Pirates were generally hanged at Execution Dock on the foreshore of the Thames near Brewhouse Lane and Wapping High Street, and the bodies would be left there until they had been covered by three tides of the river.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This was done to Captain William Kidd in 1701.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Burning at the stake was used as a punishment for women who committed treason, as in the case of Katherine Hayes, who was burned in 1726 at Tyburn for murdering her husband.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] As the period went on, this sentence changed to include being hanged before the body was burned at the stake.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Men who committed treason were sentenced to be hanged, drawn and quartered, as was the case for several soldiers who supported the 1745 Jacobite Rebellion, who were executed on Kennington Common.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Nobles who committed treason were permitted to die by beheading.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The last person to be executed by beheading in Britain was Lord Lovat on Tower Hill in 1747.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Prisoners who refused to plead either guilty or not guilty would be "pressed" to death, otherwise known as *peine forte et dure,* by being slowly crushed by large stones, a practice abolished in 1772.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] After the Transportation Act 1717, transportation became another common punishment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, convicts were transported to the American colonies, where their labour would be sold to a plantation for the duration of their sentence, but after the American Revolutionary War, the authorities looked for a new location.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London's first shipment of convicts to Australia set off in 1787, and landed in Port Jackson, in modern-day Sydney.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Some crimes were punished by whipping, which could take place either in public, tied to the back of a cart and being marched through the streets; or in the private confines of a prison.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Another punishment designed to inflict public humiliation was the pillory.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] As the century went on, those sentenced to the pillory would increasingly find themselves at the mercy of the mob, who could either protect them while they served their sentence or throw rotten vegetables, manure, dead animals, or rocks.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Several people were killed by mobs while in the pillory.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1779, a new kind of prison was introduced called the pentitentiary, with an emphasis on forcing criminals to do hard labour.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London's prisons were often filthy and its officers corrupt.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1726, an investigation into conditions in the Fleet Prison revealed that families had to bribe the warden to hand over the bodies of their family members who had died inside; and that one man called Jacob Solas had been chained up next to a sewer and a rubbish heap for two months.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1750, an outbreak of "jail fever" at the Old Bailey next to Newgate Prison killed at least 50 people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1715, claimant to the throne James Stuart landed in Scotland in what is known as the Jacobite Rebellion.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In London, his supporters rioted, burning a portrait of William III, drinking toasts to James II, and attacking those who refused to join them.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Soldiers were mobilised in Hyde Park in the event that Stuart should reach the capital.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1745, Stuart made another attempt, leading to a military camp being set up at Finchley in case the Jacobite forces reached London from Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the end, they only made it as far as Derby.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1763, the politician John Wilkes came under scrutiny after he wrote articles criticising George III.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] He was briefly imprisoned in the Tower of London, and his newspaper, the North Briton, was burned in a ritual execution outside the Royal Exchange.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] During the burning, Londoners rushed to rescue copies from the flames, and attacked the sheriff in his coach.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Later that year, the MP Samuel Martin challenged Wilkes to a duel in Hyde Park, during which he shot Wilkes in the stomach.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] When Wilkes won an election in 1768, his supporters marched through the streets from Brentford to London, and when they got there, they broke all the windows in the newly built Mansion House.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] On 10 May, a soldiers fired upon a group of Wilkes' supporters at St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] George's Fields, and several people were killed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The following year, Wilkes won a re-election, but the government nonetheless announced his opponent as the winner.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] When supporters of the government marched to St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] James's, they were pelted with mud by Wilkes' supporters.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Wilkes was so popular among Londoners that in 1774 there was a crush to be one of the people who got to pull his coach, and one man was killed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] During the American Revolutionary War, the City of London generally favoured the colonists, arguing that their taxation was too heavy and that the government should not use violence against them.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1775, the City sent a petition to the king with 1,171 signatures to this effect.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1780, London was rocked by the Gordon Riots, an uprising led by Lord George Gordon against Roman Catholic emancipation.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Severe damage was caused to Catholic churches and homes, and rioters also attacked legal buildings such as the Bow Street magistrates' court, Newgate Prison, the King's Bench Prison, the Fleet Prison, and The Clink.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Houses of Protestants who were sympathetic to Catholics, such as those of George Savile, Lord Justice Cox, and the Earl of Mansfield, were also destroyed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One newspaper at the time estimated that over 450 people were killed in the riots themselves, and 35 were executed in the aftermath, although George Gordon himself escaped the gallows.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Royal Society of Arts was founded in 1754 in Crane Court.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1774, they moved into their current address on John Adam Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Royal Academy was established in 1768 at Somerset House as an art school that ran a regular exhibition of artworks by its members.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Its first president was the painter Joshua Reynolds, and its pupils included J.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Popular London portrait artists included Arthur Devis, John Wootton, Allan Ramsay, Johann Zoffany, Thomas Gainsborough, and Joshua Reynolds.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] William Hogarth created satirical paintings such as *A Rake's Progress* that became famous as engraved prints.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] James Barry created early Romantic paintings.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Only eight visitors saw it on its first day of operation.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Mozart family arrived in London in 1764, staying at Cecil Court, Ebury Street and Frith Street, and performing in several concerts.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] During this time, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart wrote several works including his first symphony, Symphony No.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The pianoforte also appeared in London for the first time in this period, with a concert including the instrument being performed in 1767 at the Covent Garden Theatre, now known as the Royal Opera House.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] James's gentlemen's clubs date from this period, including Almack's, Brooks's, and Boodle's.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] These clubs offered society and gambling to wealthy gentlemen, and many are still in operation today.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] James's, other important gentlemen's clubs were founded such as the Kit-Cat Club, which met around the Strand and included famous Whigs of the day.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Bare-knuckle boxing, also known as prizefighting, was incredibly popular, despite being illegal.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Famous boxers included James Figg, Jack Broughton, Tom Johnson, and Daniel Mendoza.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Broughton introduced an early form of boxing gloves called "mufflers" and laid down a set of rules for his boxing arena on Tottenham Court Road in order to ensure the safety of participants.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] These rules have been called the "first written rules to be applied to any sport".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1749, London held Britain's first-known open yacht race, from Greenwich to the mouth of the Thames.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1775, the Cumberland Fleet became the first yacht club to organise races.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the 1750s, the Jockey Club was formed by aristocratic regulars at the Star and Garter Club in Pall Mall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The first attempt at codifying the rules of cricket was made by the London Cricket Club at the Artillery Ground in Finsbury in 1744.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Lord's cricket ground was founded in this period, with the wine merchant Thomas Lord leasing out a parcel of land in Islington for his friends to play cricket on in 1787.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Marylebone Cricket Club grew out of players at this venue, with the club's earliest minute books also dating back to this year.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One of the most popular places to go for entertainment in London was Vauxhall Gardens, which reopened with new management in 1732 as the "New Spring Gardens".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 18th-century Londoners could also visit assembly rooms such as the Pantheon on Oxford Street, where people could enjoy Vauxhall Garden-style activities such as dances and masquerades in all weathers.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Bull baiting and bear baiting were popular pastimes, with more exotic animals being brought in occasionally.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] For example, in 1747, a former boxer called John Broughton advertised a tiger baiting on Oxford Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Areas around London also held annual fairs, such as Bartholomew Fair and Southwark Fair, which was abolished in 1762.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One attraction of Southwark Fair was the acrobat Mr Cadman, who walked across a rope tied from building to building over the street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Occasionally, the winter was cold enough to make the Thames freeze completely, allowing for "frost fairs" on the ice, such as in 1789, when a bearbaiting took place on the ice, and an ox was roasted whole at Shadwell.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Towards the end of the period, hot air balloon flights became a regular feature of London's entertainment offering, with the first balloon launch in England taking place in 1783 at the Artillery Ground near Finsbury Square.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This first attempt was unmanned; the first manned balloon flight in the country was undertaken the following year from the same place by Vincenzo Lunardi.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Irish artist Robert Barker began this trend, and in fact coined the term *panorama,* in the 1790s.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London played host to many important writers of the 18th century such as Jonathan Swift, Alexander Pope, Henry Fielding, Edmund Burke, Oliver Goldsmith, Fanny Burney, and Daniel Defoe.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Londoners such as Mary Astell and Mary Wollstonecraft wrote early feminist works, and poets such as Stephen Duck wrote about the working-class.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Britain's first daily newspaper, the *Daily Courant*, was sold 1702–1735 from Ludgate Hill.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] *Gentleman's Magazine* began publication in 1731 and continued until 1907.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The first English Sunday newspaper, the *British Gazette and Sunday Monitor*, began publication in 1780.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] *The Times* was founded in 1785 as the *Daily Universal Register*, and *The Observer* in 1791.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1755, Samuel Johnson published one of the first dictionaries of the English language, which had taken him eight years to write from his house in Gough Square.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Johnson's dictionary attempted to be more comprehensive than previous attempts, and included quotations showing where each word had come from.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] What is now the Theatre Royal Haymarket opened in 1705 as the Queen's Theatre.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Royal Opera House first opened in 1732 as the Covent Garden Theatre.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 1728 saw the opening of *The Beggar's Opera* at Lincoln's Inn Fields.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Unlike the Italian-style operas that London audiences were used to, this used well-known folk songs and hymns from the time with the lyrics changed, so that audiences could sing along.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] It ran for 60 performances, considered a very long run at the time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] One particularly famous star of the stage in the period was David Garrick, who had his debut in 1741 at Goodman's Fields Theatre.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The famous actress Sarah Siddons first appeared at the Drury Lane Theatre in 1775, playing Portia in *The Merchant of Venice.* This period also saw the rise of famous playwrights such as Richard Brinsley Sheridan, whose play *The Rivals* opened at Covent Garden in the same year.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] After the 1737 Licensing Act, all plays where the audience were charged for tickets had to be licensed by the Lord Chamberlain, a national censorship that lasted until 1968.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Pantomime has its origins in 18th-century London theatre, with *The Tavern Bilkers* at the Theatre Royal Drury Lane in 1702 being a possible candidate for the world's first pantomime.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1720, Lady Mary Wortley Montagu returned to London from travels in the Ottoman Empire, where she acquired knowledge of smallpox inoculation.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1721, she had her three-year-daughter publicly inoculated by the surgeon Charles Maitland at the Royal College of Physicians.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This resulted in a short-lived wave of popularity for inoculation among the wealthy in London, including the Princess of Wales.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Many new people were training to become surgeons, and needed corpses to practice on and learn from.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] From 1752, the bodies of six hanged criminals were given to the Royal College of Surgeons for this purpose each year, but this was nowhere near the number required.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1767, Dr William Hunter opened a School of Anatomy in Great Windmill Street to showcase dissections for medical students.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This need created demand for a class of criminal known as bodysnatchers, who stole recently deceased bodies from graveyards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In response, some churches built watchhouses and hired guards.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Excessive drinking was a common hazard to Londoners' health, particularly during the Gin Craze in the first half of the century.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1720, London's distilleries produced 2.5 million gallons of spirits per year.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Newspapers such as the *London Journal* attributed several deaths to gin-drinking, such as that of a porter in Holborn who "drank so plentifully of Geneva, with his wife, that he died upon the spot [...] 'tis said that they drank three pints apiece, in a little more than an hour".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] A Whitechapel stationer and rag merchant, William Addis, is credited with inventing the toothbrush in 1780.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] At the beginning of the period, London had two main hospitals: St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Beginning in the 1720s, there was a movement to build new hospitals using charitable donations, which were called "voluntary" hospitals.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Donors could nominate patients to receive free treatment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1720, Westminster Hospital was opened in Petty France.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 1725 saw the opening of Guy's Hospital, which was originally intended for up to 400 poor patients with incurable conditions, which other hospitals such as St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] George's Hospital was founded in 1733, and the London Hospital in 1740.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1739, Britain's first midwifery school was opened at St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Middlesex Hospital opened in 1745 on Windmill Street with just 18 beds.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The London Hospital moved to large new buildings on Whitechapel Road in the 1750s, where they still are to this day.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] From the 1750s, there was a wave of new maternity or "lying-in" hospitals, beginning with the British Lying-In Hospital in 1749, and further examples being built in 1750, 1752, and 1765.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London had a smallpox hospital at Coldbath Fields from the 1740s, which moved to St.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London's main lunatic asylum, the Bethlehem Royal Hospital (better known as Bedlam) long predates this period, but in 1770 it banned the longstanding practice of allowing tourists to pay to view its inmates.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The hospital still operates in London to this day.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] England's first veterinary college was also founded in this period- the Royal Veterinary College, originally based in Camden in 1791.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Another way people could get medical help in this period was through dispensaries.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] A dispensary was an organisation that provided medical help using money donated by wealthy people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] These donors could then write letters of recommendation to allow poorer people to access treatment.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The first free dispensary in London was founded in Red Lion Square in 1769.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] King's Cross had several springs which were thought to have medicinal qualities.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1759, the Bagnigge Wells opened, with a pump room where visitors could drink the water, play skittles, and hear concerts.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Water could be bought for 3d per gallon.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1770, a spa was also founded in Bermondsey, near what is now known as Spa Road.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In September 1720, stock in the South Sea Company collapsed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Many wealthy Londoners lost large amounts of money (the Duke of Chandos lost £700,000), and in January 1721, one newspaper suggested that data on the number of suicides caused by the crash should be collected.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The 18th century saw the rise and fall of London's silk trade, run in chief by Protestant Huguenot families fleeing persecution in Catholic France and setting up silk looms in Spitalfields.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the 1710s, calico fabric imported from India began to undercut London silk, and in 1719, 4,000 Spitalfields silkweavers rioted in an anti-calico demonstration, throwing ink and acid at women wearing calico fabric.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Throughout the century, silk weavers continued to protest and riot against the intrusion of cheaper fabrics into their market, and against poor treatment by weaving masters.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1763, a group of silkweavers broke into their master's house, broke his looms, cut up his bolts of silk, and burned the master in effigy.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In the aftermath of one silkweavers' riot in 1769, two leaders were hanged at Newgate Prison.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Silkweavers also celebrated victories, such as the law passed in 1766 banning French silk from being imported.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Silkweavers processed through the streets playing "God Save The King", and lit bonfires and fireworks.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] A huge portion of London's economy was built through trade, particularly shipping.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1790, 70% of Britain's imports and 56% of its exports came through the capital.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Ships coming to London were required to dock at the legal quays in the "Pool of London", a complex of many tiny quays and wharves along the side of the Thames from London Bridge to the Tower.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This was extremely congested, and so throughout the period, more docks were added elsewhere along the river, such as Greenland Dock in Rotherhithe and the East India Company's dock at Blackwall.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Some London companies and individuals profited through colonial exploits around the world, notably in the Caribbean and India.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] For example, twice-Lord Mayor William Beckford was from a family of Jamaican plantation owners, at the time of his death owned 3,000 people across 13 plantations, and was supposedly the first English commoner to be a millionnaire upon his death.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The East India Company was based at Leadenhall Street, and alone accounted for 19% of British imports by value in the last quarter of the century.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The London Stock Exchange was founded in 1773 in Threadneedle Street.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The 18th century in Britain is often referred to as being subject to "turnpike mania", wherein many roads were placed in the custody of private trusts, who set up tollbooths along the road to pay for its upkeep.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] London's first turnpikes were set up in 1711: along Edgware Road from Kilburn to Hertfordshire, and the road from Highgate to Barnet.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] By 1720, there were five more: between Shoreditch and Enfield; Tyburn and Uxbridge; Kensington and Staines and Colnbrook; Southwark to Greenwich and Lewisham; and Westminster to New Cross.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Towards the end of the period, canals began to be constructed across London to allow for the movement of goods.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Limehouse Cut was opened in 1770 to allow boats from Hertfordshire to reach London's docks without having to go round the Isle of Dogs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] As bridges across the Thames were few and congested, many Londoners crossed the river on taxi-boats operated by watermen.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] These watermen sometimes held rowing races, and in 1715, a comic actor called Thomas Doggett offered a cash prize and a new coat and badge to the winner of a race between newly qualified watermen.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] This race, called Doggett's Coat and Badge, is still held annually in London to this day.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] The Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge was founded just before the beginning of this period in 1699, and ran charity schools throughout the century to provide education to London's poorest children.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] By the end of the century, there were 179 such schools in the city.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1758, the Orphan Working School was founded in Hoxton to teach children job skills such as shoemaking, as well as literacy and religion.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] In 1782, the Surrey Chapel opened on Blackfriars Road with 13 Sunday schools, which provided education for 3,000 children.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] 18th-century London saw England's first school for deaf and mute children, founded in 1792 in Bermondsey.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/18th-century-london] Several long-running adult education institutions were also founded in this period, such as the Linnean Society and the Royal Institution.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The **1902 Ibrox disaster** was the collapse of a stand at Ibrox Park (now Ibrox Stadium) in Govan (now part of Glasgow), Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The collapse caused the deaths of 25 supporters, and injuries to 500 more during an international association football match between Scotland and England on 5 April 1902 as part of the 1901–02 British Home Championship.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Ibrox Park had completed construction less than three years before the incident and was hosting its first international fixture, with the crowd estimated to be over 68,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The match was the first time that the ground had been used at more than half capacity since its opening.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Scotland entered the game needing only to avoid defeat to win the British Home Championship title.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] During the first half of the match, a section of the newly built West Tribune Stand collapsed, dropping between 200 and 300 people to the concrete floor below.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Two spectators were declared dead at the scene, and a further twenty-three died of injuries sustained in the incident soon after, the last victim dying three weeks later.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Despite the collapse, the match was eventually resumed after a break as officials feared emptying crowds could interfere with rescue attempts and lead to further panic.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The teams resumed the match, which ended in a 1–1 draw, although both the Scottish Football Association and the Football Association later agreed that the result should be voided.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] A replay was hastily organised and played a month later at Villa Park in Birmingham with all proceeds from the match being donated to a relief fund for victims of the disaster.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The disaster led to an overhaul in stadium design, with wooden terraced stands being largely replaced by earth or concrete embankments.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Founded in 1872, Rangers had played at various local grounds in the Glasgow area and had eventually settled at Kinning Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] However, the ground's capacity, originally 2,000 but later expanded to 7,000, was struggling to meet demand for the club's fixtures, and the venue's landlords eventually looked to move Rangers on to develop the site.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] To combat this, the club built the first Ibrox Park to the south of the burgh of Govan in 1887, and the new ground remained in use for twelve years.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The construction of Celtic Park by their Old Firm rivals Celtic in 1892 led Rangers to seek an improved venue to compete for the chance to host Scottish Cup finals or Scotland international matches, which could generate considerable income for the hosts, particularly fixtures against England.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Such was the fervour surrounding these international fixtures, *The Times* noted that the "attendance is limited only by the size of the ground".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The original Ibrox Park had hosted an England–Scotland match in 1892, but the subsequent four fixtures between 1894 and 1900 had been awarded to Celtic Park.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Rangers' directors sanctioned the £20,000 construction of a new Ibrox Park in an attempt to improve the facilities.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The new stadium was built partially overlapping the previous site and was officially opened on 30 December 1899 when Rangers defeated Heart of Midlothian 3–1.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Soon after opening, the ground reached a capacity of 75,000.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The construction was soon recognised by the Scottish Football Association (SFA) when the new stadium was selected to host the 1902 England–Scotland match by a single vote.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The match was the 31st meeting between the two sides and was the first to be contested by fully professional teams.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The West Tribune Stand was designed by Scottish architect Archibald Leitch, a boyhood Rangers fan who offered his services free of charge, and had a capacity of 35,913.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] However, Leitch had expressed concerns over the maximum capacity and visited the site prior to the match to inspect the stand, but a surveyor passed the ground fit for purpose.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] There had previously been reports of significant swaying in the structure.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The stand had been built using a steel framework which featured vertical beams set in concrete at the foundations.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Horizontal beams were then interlocked with wooden decking used to form a step-like construction for spectators to stand on.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] There were 96 steps in total, each measuring four inches in height and around fourteen inches wide.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] It was estimated that at full capacity, each spectator had on average a personal space measuring sixteen inches long and fourteen inches wide.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The 1901–02 British Home Championship began in February 1902 with Ireland defeating Wales.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Scotland played their first match of the competition on 1 March, defeating Ireland 5–1 in Belfast, while reigning holders England were held to a goalless draw in their first fixture two days later against Wales.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Scotland and England both won their second matches; the Scots defeated Wales 5–1 while England beat Ireland 1–0 a week later.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] With only one match to be played Scotland led the group by a single point, needing only to avoid defeat against England at Ibrox to win their second title in three seasons.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] On 5 April 1902, the final match of the season's British Home Championship between Scotland and England kicked off at 3:30pm.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] There was no official count of the attendance, but estimated figures for the match state there was a crowd of more than 68,000 in attendance, half of whom were standing in the West Tribune Stand.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] There were around 50 stewards on duty for the match, most of whom were experienced in their role and had been provided by the SFA.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Although they had no way of determining when the stand was full, they had been given signs declaring the stand full that were displayed at an appropriate time.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The stand had never previously held as many supporters, never being more than half full in previous uses.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Early in the match, supporters briefly surged toward the front of the terracing, and the on-duty police were forced to intervene in order to regulate the crowd and disperse them from one area.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Newspaper reports and later studies place the incident occurring around 30 minutes into the first half of the match, when the back of the newly built West Tribune Stand collapsed, sending hundreds of supporters up to 40 feet (12 metres) to the ground below.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Several factors have been reasoned for the collapse, including heavy rainfall the previous night and the large crowd stamping and swaying as the match progressed.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] One theory in a report following the event centred around Scottish player Bobby Templeton.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Regarded as an exciting attacking player, Templeton was making his debut for the Scotland national team and had gained possession of the ball moments prior to the collapse.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The investigation stated that the crowd's desperation to see Templeton dribble with the ball caused them to surge forward, which may have contributed to the collapse.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] It was also noted that the bottom ten rows of the stand had been left vacant as people had filled the racing track surrounding the pitch.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] This blocked the view from these rows and resulted in the spectators on the lower rows to continually press upwards to avoid being pushed into the empty rows below them and lose their vantage points.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] An investigation of the scene afterwards found that seventeen joints had given way, causing a hole approximately 20 yards (18 metres) long to open up in the stand.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Several witnesses in the crowd reported hearing loud cracking noises prior to the collapse, and one witness, who worked as a joiner, claimed to have seen the wooden boards split prior to the collapse.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Immediately following the collapse, the crowd around the hole fled onto the playing field in an attempt to escape the stand.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Scottish player Alex Raisbeck later stated that the players were unaware of the incident and initially believed that the surging crowd was a pitch invasion as supporters scrambled over the railings surrounding the field.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] He would later describe the scene, stating "When we saw the ambulance men at work we knew that something serious had happened.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] We were told to retire to the dressing-rooms.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Dead bodies and groaning men were lying on the seats where only a short time ago the Scottish players had stripped.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Officials estimated that between 200 and 300 spectators fell through the hole to the ground below.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The majority of fatal injuries that occurred were directly caused by people impacting with either the ground or the steel girders as they fell.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The mass of people eventually became heaped on the ground, with historians from the Western Infirmary in Glasgow, where the deceased were taken, commenting "Those who first reached the ground alive must then have been at hazard from suffocation" due to the volume of people.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Newspaper reporters visiting the scene in the following days remarked on the lack of debris at the site as vast amounts of the shattered metal and wood had been used to form makeshift stretchers to carry injured spectators.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Despite the chaos, match officials feared that abandoning the match would lead to further injury if supporters began exiting the stadium en masse and could hinder the rescue attempts.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Representatives of the SFA and the Football Association hastily discussed how to proceed and instead chose to resume the match after a twenty-minute delay.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] *The Scotsman* noted how, on one occasion, mounted police officers had to be asked to move in order for a free kick to be taken.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Scottish goalkeeper Ned Doig was reported to have wept consistently throughout the second half of the match.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] A significant number of spectators were unaware of the severity of the incident and, despite the gates being thrown open upon the incident in fear of a crush developing, few chose to leave the ground.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] In total, 25 people died and over 500 were reported as injured, ranging between "dangerously" and "slightly".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The most common cause of death was listed as a fracture at the base of the skull, with fourteen of the victims being recorded under this category.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Two of the fourteen, Alexander Murray and Bruce Crawford, were listed as "instantaneous" and were the only two victims to be pronounced dead at Ibrox Park itself.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] By the end of the day, a total of eight people had been confirmed dead.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Eight victims were listed with causes of death pertaining to crush injuries sustained by the large mass of bodies, such as severe internal chest injuries and broken ribs.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The remaining three deaths were attributed to either shock or cardiac arrest.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The final victim, Peter Patterson, died five weeks after the disaster on 15 May.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Two weeks after the disaster, *The Scotsman* issued a list of injuries that read "dangerously injured 24, seriously injured 168, injured 153, slightly injured 171" totalling 517 injuries in total.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Other reports put the injured as high as 588.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] A large number of injuries were described as cuts and gashes to the heads of spectators, believed to have been caused by the jagged edging of the wooden decking left by the collapse.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] William Dewar from Kirkcaldy was also seriously injured in the disaster and the *Dundee Evening Telegraph* reported that he never recovered from his injuries before dying suddenly in July 1904.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Another spectator, Donald Smith, died in July 1905 which was also attributed to injuries sustained in the disaster.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The disaster was considered the first major incident of its kind, with the *Athletic News* writing "the one solacing reflection is that this is the only case of fatality of this kind in connection with (the) sport".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] It remained the deadliest stadium disaster in Britain until the Burnden Park disaster in Bolton in March 1946.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] No charges were brought against Rangers or the SFA over the incident.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] A criminal investigation into the disaster did bring charges against timber merchant Alexander McDougall, who was charged with culpable homicide in June of the same year.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] McDougall had supplied the wood used in the construction of the stand and was accused of attempting to cut corners by using yellow pine instead of the higher-quality red pine.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Noted civil engineers Sir Benjamin Baker and Sir William Arrol appeared as witnesses in McDougall's defence.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Both testified that they believed the selection of yellow pine had played no part in the disaster and instead blamed the accident on the construction of the stand.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The design was deemed too light for the work for which it was built, having been based on out-of-date textbooks.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Baker concluded that the stand's design made it safe for a load of 25 lb per square foot (122 kg/m2) but estimated that on the day of the match it had experienced loads of up to 75 lb per square foot (366 kg/m2).
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] McDougall was later unanimously acquitted of the charge.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Following the accident, the use of wooden frameworks on steel frames for football grounds was largely discredited, and replaced throughout the United Kingdom by terracing supported by earthworks or reinforced concrete.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Rangers had won four consecutive Scottish league championships prior to the disaster, but following the accident the club sold several of their best players to raise funds for a major redevelopment of Ibrox.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Rangers did not win another league championship until 1911.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] On 19 April 1902, a meeting of the FA Council declared that the match would be officially listed as "unfinished".
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] During the meeting, it was also agreed for a relief fund to be created for victims and their families, with the FA donating £500 themselves, and a replay match organised, with all proceeds being donated to the fund.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The replay was held four weeks later at Villa Park in Birmingham on 3 May 1902 and ended in a 2–2 draw, with the majority of the players remaining unchanged from the original match, Scotland making three changes.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The result secured the British Home Championship title for Scotland.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] An Ibrox Park disaster fund was established in aid of the victims and ran for nearly two years before being disbanded.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] During its operation, the fund paid out nearly £18,000 to injured spectators and more than £5,000 to the families of the deceased.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The remaining funds, totaling around £5,500, were used to pay administrative costs before being donated to the infirmaries which had treated the injured spectators.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Ibrox underwent substantial redevelopments following the disaster.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] By the end of 1902, the West Tribune Stand had been significantly lowered in height to match the other stands.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] The number of beams in the stand was trebled which was designed to make it impossible for a spectator to fall through, even if the boards should give way.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Matches also resumed the same year but with limited capacity in all stands.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] During 1963, concerns were raised about the safety of the stairway adjacent to passageway 13 (colloquially known as Stairway 13), the exit closest to Copland Road subway station.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] On 16 September 1961 two people were killed in a crush on the stairway, and there were two other incidents, in 1967 and 1969, where several people were injured.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Rangers had by then spent a total of £150,000 on improvements.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1902-ibrox-disaster] Despite this, another larger disaster occurred at Ibrox in 1971, when 66 people were killed in a crush as supporters tried to leave the stadium at an Old Firm match.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:1966-fifa-world-cup-final/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
